# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alzheimer-s-disease
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] It was a major success domestically, topping the box office for two consecutive weeks to become the 5th highest-grossing film of 2004.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] The film was also a hit in Japan, breaking previous records of Korean films released there; it was the 19th highest-grossing film at the 2005 Japanese box office.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Lee and Kim Young-ha won Best Adapted Screenplay at the 2005 Grand Bell Awards.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] The film was remade in Turkish as *Evim Sensin* in 2012 and in Hindi as *Saiyaara* in 2025.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] The first act of the film introduces the two main characters: a woman named Su-jin and a man named Chul-soo.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] The film highlights their accidental meeting, followed by their subsequent courtship despite their social differences that should have kept them apart.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Su-jin is a 27-year-old fashion designer who has been rejected by her lover, a married colleague.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Depressed, she goes to a convenience store where she bumps into a tall, handsome man, with whom she has a brief misunderstanding.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Afterwards, she returns home, receives her father's forgiveness and decides to start her life over.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] One day, while accompanying her father — the CEO of a construction firm — she coincidentally meets the man she bumped into at the convenience store earlier.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] His name is Choi Chul-soo and he is the construction site's foreman, as well as being a student architect.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Although he initially seems like a rough, dirty construction worker, Chul-soo exudes pure masculinity.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Su-jin instantly takes a liking to him and actively courts him.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Many sweet events take place during their courtship, eventually leading to their marriage.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] The second act sees the couple happily settling into married life.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Chul-soo designs their dream house, while Su-jin learns to become a housewife.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] However, as time passes, Su-jin begins to display signs of forgetfulness.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] In one incident, a fire breaks out because she has forgotten to turn off the stove.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Although Chul-soo managed to extinguish the fire in time, the seriousness of this and similar incidents led them to seek medical help.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] The third act deals with Su-jin's diagnosis of early-onset Alzheimer's disease, and how the couple respond to it.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Initially in denial, Su-jin is eventually overwhelmed by the knowledge that she will forget her husband.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Nevertheless, they commit to staying together, and as the disease progresses and Su-jin's memory deteriorates, the couple face increasing challenges.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Ultimately, Su-jin decides to leave their home and check into an assisted living facility.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Despite his grief, Chul-soo stays by Su-jin's side, even when she doesn't recognise him.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] He hides his tears behind sunglasses so she can't see them.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] At the end of the film, Chul-soo recreates the moment they first met in the convenience store, with Su-jin's friends and family present.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] On October 22, 2008, it was reported that CBS Films had secured the rights for an American remake, with Susannah Grant attached to write the screenplay.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] After a turnaround, it was announced in February 2013 that Scott Pictures will produce and finance along with Sobini Films and Film 360 with Ben Lewin set to direct and Katherine Heigl has been cast as the female lead.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] On August 30, 2016, Josh Hartnett was in talks to star in the remake and Jena Malone replaced Heigl.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] As of 2021, shooting of the film started as of November 2021, and the official title of the film was renamed to "Special Memory".
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] By May 2023, it was announced that film was delayed due to scheduling conflicts with their projects and production issues.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Alonzo was replaced by Julia Barretto in their role.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] By August 2025, the remake went in an overhaul, with GMA Pictures exiting the project, recast all main cast and rehired a new director.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/a-moment-to-remember] Bela Padilla and Carlo Aquino serves as the main cast, while Jerry Sineneng serves as the director of the remake.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] AA amyloidosis is a complication of a number of inflammatory diseases and infections, although only a small portion of patients with these conditions will go on to develop AA amyloidosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] The most common presentation of AA amyloidosis is renal in nature, including proteinuria, nephrotic syndrome and progressive development of chronic kidney disease leading to end stage kidney disease (ESKD) and need for renal replacement therapy (e.g. dialysis or kidney transplantation).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] Signs and symptoms of amyloidosis can vary depending on the affected organ.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] AA amyloidosis commonly affects kidneys, liver, and stomach.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] In a healthy individual, the median plasma concentration of SAA is 3 mg per liter.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] This can increase to over 2000 mg per liter during an acute phase response and a sustained overproduction of SAA is required for the creation of the AA deposits that define AA amyloidosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] High levels of SAA, however, is not a sufficient condition for the development of systemic AA amyloidosis and it remains unclear what triggers the accumulation of AA.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] The AA protein is mainly deposited in the liver, spleen and kidney, and AA amyloidosis can lead to nephrotic syndrome and ESRD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] Natural history studies show, however, that it is the kidney involvement that drives the progression of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] In general, old age, reduced serum albumin concentration, end stage kidney failure, and sustained elevated SAA concentration are all associated with poor prognosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] Tissue biopsy using subcutaneous abdominal fat tissue aspiration is typically used as it is safe and sensitive.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] It is also possible to biopsy the rectal mucosa or minor salivary glands.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] Amyloidosis is confirmed by histological identification of amyloid deposits.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] At this point, amyloid typing with immunochemical staining is necessary, as the differential diagnosis includes AA amyloidosis, AL amyloidosis, hereditary amyloidosis, dialysis-related amyloidosis and age-related systemic amyloidosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] Testing of serum and urine for monoclonal immunoglobulins and of serum for free light chains may help rule out immunoglobulin light chain amyloidosis, while genetic testing may be used if hereditary amyloidosis is suspected.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] There are currently no approved treatments for systemic AA amyloidosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] The current standard of care includes treatments for the underlying inflammatory disease with anti-inflammatory drugs, immunosuppressive agents or biologics.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] AA amyloidosis patients are also receiving treatments to slow down the decline of their renal function, such as angiotensin II receptor blockers or angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitors.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] There is evidence that eating amyloid fibers may lead to amyloidosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] This evidence is based on studies in cattle, chickens, mice, and cheetahs.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] Thus, in a sense, SAA amyloidosis may be considered a contagious disease, although whether this occurs or is important in the development of naturally occurring amyloidosis remains unknown.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/aa-amyloidosis] Nevertheless, because amyloid fibers can be detected in muscle in low amounts, it raises some concern about whether people could develop amyloidosis as a result of ingesting meat from an animal with the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] The protein encoded by this gene is a member of the superfamily of ATP-binding cassette (ABC) transporters.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] ABC proteins transport various molecules across extra- and intra-cellular membranes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] ABC genes are divided into seven distinct subfamilies: ABC1, MDR/TAP, CFTR/MRP, ALD (adrenoleukodystrophy), OABP, GCN20, and White.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] This protein is a member of the ABC1 subfamily.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] Members of the ABC1 subfamily comprise the only major ABC subfamily found exclusively in multicellular eukaryotes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] This full transporter has been detected predominantly in myelo-lymphatic tissues with the highest expression in peripheral leukocytes, thymus, spleen, and bone marrow.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] The function of this protein is not yet known; however, the expression pattern suggests a role in lipid homeostasis in cells of the immune system.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] Alternative splicing of this gene results in two transcript variants.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] Lack of ABCA7 gene exhibits phenotypes in mice, such as moderate decrease in plasma HDL and adipose tissues only in female, while release of cellular cholesterol and phospholipid is not impaired.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] Accordingly, decrease in plasma lectin level was also reported.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] Reduction of CD3 or CD1d may lead to dysfunction of T cells by deletion of ABCA7.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] On the other hand, transfected and expressed ABCA7, but not endogenous ABCA7, mediates release of cell phospholipid and cholesterol to generate HDL-like particles but contain less cholesterol than those generated by ABCA1.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] ABCA7-generated HDL is smaller and appears as a single peak in a molecular sieve HPLC analysis in comparison to HDL generated by ABCA1 that shows twin peaks of small and poor in cholesterol and large and rich in cholesterol.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] ABCA7 mRNA generates full length cDNA and a spliced form of cDNA, and only the former is capable of generating HDL when transfected.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] ABCA7 was shown associated with cellular phagocytotic activity.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] The promoter of ABCA7 contains sterol regulatory element (SRE) so that ABCA7 is down-regulated by cell cholesterol through sterol regulatory element binding protein (SREBP) 2.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] Therefore, ABCA7 expression and phagocytosis are up-regulated by use of HMG-reductase inhibitors (statins).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] In addition, ABCA7 is stabilized like ABCA1 by helical apolipoproteins such as apoA-I, and phagocytosis is accordingly increased in such a condition.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] In summary, ABCA7 is a substantially related protein to ABCA1 but it does not mediate cell cholesterol release by generation of HDL unless it is externally transfected and expressed in vitro.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] ABCA7 is shown associated with cellular phagocytotic function in vivo and in vitro, and expression of the ABCA7 gene is regulated by cell cholesterol mainly through the SRE/SREBP system in a negative feed-back fashion in contrast to positive feedback by the LXR/RXR system for ABCA1.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] ABCA7 thus links cholesterol metabolism to host defense system.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] In 2011, two genome-wide association studies (GWAS) identified ABCA7 as a new susceptibility locus for late-onset Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] The finding was also confirmed by other meta-analysis investigations later.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] Such association of ABCA7 variants was reported on more specific findings of the disease such as memory decline and incident mild cognitive impairment or cortical and hippocampal atrophy.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] Protein-disrupting variants in ABCA7 have been shown to predispose to Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] The Icelandic database of Decode Genetics has shown a doubled probability of developing Alzheimer's disease when inactive variants of the ABCA7 gene are present.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] By using the knock-out mice, ABCA7 was indicated involved in generation and processing of amyloid β (Aβ) peptides.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] In the brain of the amyloid precursor protein transgenic mice, deletion of ABCA7 resulted in accumulation of Aβ40 and Aβ42 in the early stage apparently by accelerating Aβ production.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] More rapid endocytosis of amyloid precursor protein was observed in primary microglia from ABCA7 deficient mice.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] Roles of ABCA7 are also implicated for microglial phagocytotic function and immune responses.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] Although the direct target of ABCA7 function is unclear, the findings are so far mechanistically consistent with the increased Aβ production.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/abca7] Since ABCA7 gene is down-regulated by cell cholesterol via the SRE/SREBP system, the data accumulated are consistent with clinical implication that use of statins, HMG-CoA reductase inhibitors, reduces risk for Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] AL amyloidosis can affect a wide range of organs, and consequently present with a range of symptoms.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Non-specific symptoms may include fatigue and weight loss.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] The kidneys are commonly affected in systemic AL amyloidosis with 60–70% of people having kidney involvement.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Symptoms of kidney disease and kidney failure can include fluid retention, swelling, and shortness of breath.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Other manifestations of kidney involvement may include protein loss in the urine, low albumin levels in the blood and secondary hyperlipidemia (nephrotic syndrome).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Kidney damage in AL amyloidosis may progress to end stage disease requiring dialysis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] 70–80% of those with AL amyloidosis have heart involvement, and heart involvement is the leading cause of death.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Heart complications, include heart failure and irregular heart beat.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Early heart involvement in AL amyloidosis may present as low voltage electrical rhythms on an electrocardiograph, concentric left ventricular hypertrophy and diastolic dysfunction.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] A person may progress to overt heart failure due to cardiomyopathy as amyloid fibril deposition in the heart muscle progresses.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Further signs of cardiac involvement in AL amyloidosis include heart arrhythmias (bradycardia, ventricular tachycardia) which may necessitate pacemaker or implantable defibrillator placement and reduced contractility of the atria, with the associated risk of atrial blood clots.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Other organ systems that may be involved include gastrointestinal tract, blood, lungs and skin.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Other symptoms can include stroke, gastrointestinal disorders, enlarged liver, diminished spleen function, diminished function of the adrenal and other endocrine glands, skin color change or growths, lung problems, or bleeding and bruising problems.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] An enlarged tongue, or macroglossia, is sometimes seen in AL amyloidosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] AL amyloidosis is caused by the deposition of abnormal antibody free light chains.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] The abnormal light chains are produced by monoclonal plasma cells, and, although AL amyloidosis can occur without diagnosis of another disorder, it is often associated with other plasma cell disorders, such as multiple myeloma and Waldenström's macroglobulinemia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] About 10% to 15% of patients with multiple myeloma may develop overt AL amyloidosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] AL amyloidosis is not considered to be hereditary.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Diagnosis of AL amyloidosis requires identification of amyloid deposits within a tissue sample and confirmation of a plasma cell disorder.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Both blood and urine can be tested for the light chains which form amyloid deposits, however the diagnosis requires a sample of an amyloid deposit.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] A fine needle aspiration (FNA) may be done of the abdominal fat pad (which commonly contains amyloid deposits) to aid in the diagnosis of AL amyloidosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] FNA of the abdominal fat pad shows amyloid deposits in 70-75% of cases of suspected AL amyloidosis and diagnosed 85% of cases when combined with a bone marrow biopsy.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Other peripheral areas such as the salivary glands, gingiva, rectum or skin may also be biopsied, however in some cases a biopsy of the target organ may be needed.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] On microscopic exam of biopsy specimens, amyloid deposits appear green ("apple-green birefringence") when stained with Congo Red dye and viewed under polarized light.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Disordered plasma cells with a monoclonal protein product (immunoglobulin light chains) are confirmed in AL amyloidosis using serum or urine protein electrophoresis, immunoglobulin free light-chain assays or identification of lambda or kappa restricted plasma cells on a bone marrow biopsy.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] The precursor protein that is forming the amyloid fibrils may be identified using immunohistochemical studies such as immunofluorescence or immunostaining, immunogold electron microscopy or mass spectroscopy (which is not widely available).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Mass spectroscopy has a sensitivity of 88% and a specificity of 96% in identifying the precursor protein in AL amyloidosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Cardiac involvement in AL amyloidosis may be assessed using echocardiography, cardiac magnetic resonance (cardiac MRI) or positron emission tomography (PET scan).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] The most effective treatment is autologous bone marrow transplants with stem cell rescues.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] However many patients are too weak to tolerate this approach.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Other treatments can involve application of chemotherapy similar to that used in multiple myeloma, which targets the plasma cells responsible for producing the misfolded light chain proteins.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] The most widely used regiment, and first line therapy, for those ineligible for a stem cell transplant is cyclophosphamide, bortezomib and dexamethasone (CyBorD) with daratumumab added.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Daratumumab, a monoclonal antibody to CD38, a protein that is expressed on plasma cells, was approved in US and EU for AL Amyloidosis in 2021.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] CyBorD with daratumumab has a 78% very good partial hematologic response rate or better as well as a 55-55% organ response rate (reductions in organ damage) at 18 months, with the addition of daratumumab to CyBorD being associated with improved outcomes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] CyBorD may be used alone, or bortezomib–melphalan–dexamethasone may be used in resource limited settings where daratumumab is not available.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Birtamimab and anselamimab are monoclonal antibodies which are currently undergoing trials.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] The two antibodies work by targeting the misfolded immunoglobulin light chains making up the amyloid fibrils and designating them for destruction by macrophages, thus degrading amyloid microfibril deposits.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Supportive care in AL amyloidosis consists of salt restriction and diuretics in those with heart failure or kidney involvement.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] An angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitor (ACEi) or angiotensin receptor blocker (ARB) may be used in those with significant proteinuria due to kidney disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Amiodarone or an implantable defibrillator are sometimes needed for those with cardiomyopathy due to AL amyloidosis who are at risk of ventricular arrhythmias.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Those with AL amyloidosis and kidney disease may require dialysis if kidney involvement progresses.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Median survival for patients diagnosed with AL amyloidosis was 13 months in the early 1990s, but had improved to about 40 months a decade later with 5 year survival rates also increasing from 15% in the 1980s to 48% in the mid 2010s .
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Heart involvement is associated with a worse prognosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] AL amyloidosis is a rare disease; only 1200 to 3200 new cases are reported each year in the United States, and between 500 and 600 in the UK.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/al-amyloidosis] Two thirds of patients with AL amyloidosis are male and less than 5% of patients are under 40 years of age.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Most cases of ALS (about 90–95%) have no known cause and are known as *sporadic ALS*.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Genetic, autoimmune, and environmental factors are believed to be involved in the onset of ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Approximately 5–10% of ALS cases have a known genetic cause and are often linked to a family history of ALS; such cases are known as *familial ALS* or hereditary ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Mutations in the C9orf72 gene are the most common known genetic cause of familial ALS and are also found in a subset of sporadic cases.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Four disease-linked genes are responsible for approximately half of all genetic cases.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The goal of treatment is to slow the disease progression and improve symptoms.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] FDA-approved treatments that slow the progression of ALS include riluzole and edaravone.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Non-invasive ventilation may result in both improved quality and length of life.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Mechanical ventilation can prolong survival but does not stop disease progression.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] A feeding tube may help maintain weight and nutrition.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Death is usually caused by respiratory failure.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The disease can affect people of any age, but usually starts around the age of 60.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The average survival from onset to death is two to four years, though this can vary; about 10% of those affected survive longer than ten years.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Descriptions of the disease date back to at least 1824 by Charles Bell.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In 1869, the connection between the symptoms and the underlying neurological problems was first described by French neurologist Jean-Martin Charcot, who in 1874 began using the term *amyotrophic lateral sclerosis*.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] ALS is a motor neuron disease, which are a group of neurological disorders that selectively affect motor neurons, the cells that control voluntary muscles of the body.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Related motor neuron diseases, sometimes characterized as ALS variants rather than distinct entities, include primary lateral sclerosis (PLS), progressive muscular atrophy (PMA), progressive bulbar palsy, pseudobulbar palsy, and monomelic amyotrophy (MMA).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] As a disease, ALS may be classified in several different ways: by which part of the motor neurons is affected; by the parts of the body first affected; whether it is genetic; and by the age at which it started.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Each individual diagnosed with the condition will sit at a unique place at the intersection of these complex and overlapping subtypes, which presents a challenge to diagnosis, understanding, and prognosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] ALS can be classified by the types of motor neurons that are affected.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] To successfully control any voluntary muscle in the body, a signal must be sent from the motor cortex in the brain down the upper motor neuron as it travels down the spinal cord.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] There, it connects via a synapse to the lower motor neuron, which connects to the muscle itself.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Damage to either the upper or lower motor neuron, as it makes its way from the brain to the muscle, causes different types of symptoms.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Damage to the upper motor neuron typically causes spasticity including stiffness and increased tendon reflexes or clonus, while damage to the lower motor neuron typically causes weakness, muscle atrophy, and fasciculations.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Classical or classic ALS involves degeneration to both the upper motor neurons in the brain and the lower motor neurons in the spinal cord.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Primary lateral sclerosis (PLS) involves degeneration of primarily the upper motor neurons, and progressive muscular atrophy (PMA) involves the lower motor neurons primarily.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] There is debate over whether PLS and PMA are separate diseases or variants of ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Classical ALS accounts for about 70% of all cases of ALS and can be subdivided into cases where symptoms first appear, as these are usually focused on one region of the body at initial presentation before later spread.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] *Limb-onset* ALS (also known as spinal-onset) and *bulbar-onset* ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Limb-onset ALS begins with weakness in the hands, arms, feet, and/or legs and accounts for about two-thirds of all classical ALS cases.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Bulbar-onset ALS begins with weakness in the muscles of speech, chewing, and swallowing and accounts for about 25% of classical ALS cases.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] A rarer type of classical ALS affecting about 3% of patients is respiratory-onset, in which the initial symptoms are difficulty breathing (dyspnea) upon exertion, at rest, or while lying flat (orthopnea).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Primary lateral sclerosis (PLS) accounts for about 5% of all ALS cases and only affects the upper motor neurons in the arms, legs, and bulbar region.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] However, more than 75% of people with apparent PLS go on to later develop lower motor neuron signs within four years of symptom onset, meaning that a definitive diagnosis of PLS cannot be made until several years have passed.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] PLS has a better prognosis than classical ALS, as it progresses more slowly, results in less functional decline, does not affect the ability to breathe, and causes less severe weight loss than classical ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Progressive muscular atrophy (PMA) accounts for about 5% of all ALS cases and affects lower motor neurons in the arms, legs, and bulbar region.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] While PMA is associated with longer survival on average than classical ALS, it is still progressive over time, eventually leading to respiratory failure and death.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] As with PLS, PMA can also develop into classical ALS over time if the lower motor neuron involvement progresses to include upper motor neurons, in which case the diagnosis might be changed to classic ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Rarely, ALS symptoms may be limited to a single region of the body for an extended period of time.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The disease typically progresses more slowly than classical ALS and is associated with longer survival.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] These regional variants of ALS can only be considered as a diagnosis should the initial symptoms fail to spread to other spinal cord regions for at least 12 months.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Flail arm syndrome is characterized by lower motor neuron damage affecting the arm muscles, typically starting with the upper arms symmetrically and progressing downwards to the hands.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Flail leg syndrome is characterized by lower motor neuron damage leading to asymmetrical weakness and wasting in the legs starting around the feet.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Isolated bulbar palsy is characterized by upper or lower motor neuron damage in the bulbar region (in the absence of limb symptoms for at least 20 months), leading to gradual onset of difficulty with speech (dysarthria) and swallowing (dysphagia).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] ALS can also be classified based on the age of onset.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] People with familial ALS have an age of onset about 5 years younger than those with apparently sporadic ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] About 10% of all cases of ALS begin before age 45 ("young-onset" ALS), and about 1% of all cases begin before age 25 ("juvenile" ALS).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] People who develop young-onset ALS are more likely to be male, less likely to have bulbar onset of symptoms, and more likely to have a slower progression of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Juvenile ALS is more likely to be genetic in origin than adult-onset ALS; the most common genes associated with juvenile ALS are *FUS*, *ALS2*, and *SETX*.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Although most people with juvenile ALS live longer than those with adult-onset ALS, some of them have specific mutations in *FUS* and *SOD1* that are associated with a poor prognosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Late onset (after age 65) is generally associated with a more rapid functional decline and shorter survival.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The disorder causes muscle weakness, atrophy, and muscle spasms throughout the body due to the degeneration of the upper motor and lower motor neurons.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Sensory nerves and the autonomic nervous system are generally unaffected, meaning the majority of people with ALS maintain hearing, sight, touch, smell, and taste.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Early signs of ALS may be so subtle that the symptoms are overlooked.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The earliest symptoms of ALS are muscle weakness or muscle atrophy, typically on one side of the body.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Other presenting symptoms include trouble swallowing or breathing, cramping, or stiffness of affected muscles; muscle weakness affecting an arm or a leg; or slurred and nasal speech.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The parts of the body affected by early symptoms of ALS depend on which motor neurons in the body are damaged first.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In limb-onset ALS, the first symptoms are in the arms or the legs.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] If the legs are affected first, people may experience awkwardness, tripping, or stumbling when walking or running; this is often marked by walking with a "dropped foot" that drags gently on the ground.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] If the arms are affected first, they may experience difficulty with tasks requiring manual dexterity, such as buttoning a shirt, writing, or turning a key in a lock.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In bulbar-onset ALS, the first symptoms are difficulty speaking or swallowing.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Speech may become slurred, nasal in character, or quieter.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] There may be difficulty with swallowing and loss of tongue mobility.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] A smaller proportion of people experience "respiratory-onset" ALS, where the intercostal muscles that support breathing are affected first.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Over time, people experience increasing difficulty moving, swallowing (dysphagia), and speaking or forming words (dysarthria).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Symptoms of upper motor neuron involvement include tight and stiff muscles (spasticity) and exaggerated reflexes (hyperreflexia), including an overactive gag reflex.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] While the disease does not cause pain directly, pain is a symptom experienced by most people with ALS, caused by reduced mobility, and possibly also some sensory nerve dysfunction.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Symptoms of lower motor neuron degeneration include muscle weakness and atrophy, muscle cramps, and fleeting twitches of muscles that can be seen under the skin (fasciculations).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Although the initial site of symptoms and subsequent rate of disability progression vary from person to person, the initially affected body region is usually the most affected over time, and symptoms usually spread to a neighbouring body region.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] For example, symptoms starting in one arm usually spread to either the opposite arm or to the leg on the same side.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Bulbar-onset patients most typically experience their next symptoms in their arms rather than legs, arm-onset patients typically spread to the legs before the bulbar region, and leg-onset patients typically spread to the arms rather than the bulbar region.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Over time, regardless of where symptoms began, most people eventually lose the ability to walk or use their hands and arms independently.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] They may also lose the ability to speak and to swallow food.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] It is the eventual development of weakness of the respiratory muscles, with the loss of ability to cough and to breathe without mechanical support, that is ultimately life-shortening in ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The rate of progression can be measured using the ALS Functional Rating Scale - Revised (ALSFRS-R), a 12-item instrument survey administered as a clinical interview or self-reported questionnaire that produces a score between 48 (normal function) and 0 (severe disability).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The ALSFRS-R is the most frequently used outcome measure in clinical trials and is used by doctors to track disease progression.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] On average, people with ALS lose about 1 ALSFRS-R point per month.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Brief periods of stabilization ("plateaus") and even small reversals in ALSFRS-R score are not uncommon, owing to the subjective nature of scoring, effects of symptomatic medication, and patients' own compensations for changes in function.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] However, it is rare (<1%) for these improvements to be large (i.e. greater than 4 ALSFRS-R points) or sustained (i.e. greater than 12 months).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] A survey-based study among clinicians showed that they rated a 20% change in the slope of the ALSFRS-R as being clinically meaningful, hence its common usage as a threshold to determine efficacy of new treatments in clinical trials.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Difficulties with chewing and swallowing make eating very difficult (dysphagia) and increase the risk of choking or of aspirating food into the lungs.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In later stages of the disorder, aspiration pneumonia can develop, and maintaining a healthy weight can become a significant problem that may require the insertion of a feeding tube.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] As the diaphragm and intercostal muscles of the rib cage that support breathing weaken, measures of lung function such as vital capacity and inspiratory pressure diminish.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In respiratory-onset ALS, this may occur before significant limb weakness is apparent.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Individuals affected by the disorder may ultimately lose the ability to initiate and control all voluntary movement, known as locked-in syndrome.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Bladder and bowel function are usually spared, meaning urinary and fecal incontinence are uncommon, although trouble getting to a toilet can lead to difficulties.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The extraocular muscles responsible for eye movement are usually spared, meaning the use of eye tracking technology to support augmentative communication is often feasible.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Despite these challenges, many people in an advanced state of disease report satisfactory well-being and quality of life with these supportive measures.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Although respiratory support using non-invasive ventilation can ease problems with breathing and prolong survival, it does not affect the progression rate of ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Most people with ALS die between two and four years after the diagnosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] About 50% of people with ALS die within 30 months of their symptoms beginning, about 20% live between five and ten years, and about 10% survive for 10 years or longer.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The most common cause of death among people with ALS is respiratory failure, often accelerated by pneumonia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Most ALS patients die at home after a period of worsening difficulty breathing, a decline in their nutritional status, or a rapid worsening of symptoms.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Sudden death or acute respiratory distress are uncommon.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Access to palliative care is recommended from an early stage to explore options, ensure psychosocial support for the patient and caregivers, and to discuss advance healthcare directives.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] As with cancer staging, ALS has staging systems numbered between 1 and 4 that are used for research purposes in clinical trials.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Two very similar staging systems emerged around a similar time: the King's staging system and Milano-Torino (MiToS) functional staging.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Providing individual patients with a precise prognosis is not currently possible, though research is underway to provide statistical models on the basis of prognostic factors, including age at onset, progression rate, site of onset, and presence of frontotemporal dementia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Those with respiratory-onset ALS had a shorter median survival of 1.4 years and 0% survival at 10 years.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Though notable astrophysicist Stephen Hawking lived for 55 more years following his diagnosis, his case was an unusual one.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Cognitive impairment or behavioral dysfunction is present in 30–50% of individuals with ALS, and can appear more frequently in later stages of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Language dysfunction, executive dysfunction, and troubles with social cognition and verbal memory are the most commonly reported cognitive symptoms in ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Cognitive impairment is found more frequently in patients with C9orf72 gene repeat expansions, bulbar onset, bulbar symptoms, family history of ALS and/or a predominantly upper motor neuron phenotype.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Pseudobulbar affect and emotional lability are a type of symptom in which patients cry, smile, yawn, or laugh, either in the absence of emotional stimuli, or when they are feeling the opposite emotion to that being expressed.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Approximately half of ALS patients experience this; it is more common in those with bulbar-onset ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] While more or less benign relative to other symptoms, it can cause increased stigma and social isolation as people around the patient struggle to react appropriately to what can be frequent and inappropriate outbursts in public.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In addition to mild changes in cognition that may only emerge during neuropsychological testing, around 10–15% of individuals have signs of frontotemporal dementia (FTD).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Repeating phrases or gestures, apathy, and loss of inhibition are the most frequently reported behavioral features of ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] ALS and FTD are now considered to be part of a common disease spectrum (ALS–FTD) because of genetic, clinical, and pathological similarities.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Cognitive and behavioral issues are associated with a poorer prognosis as they may reduce adherence to medical advice and deficits in empathy and social cognition, which may increase caregiver burden.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Sporadic ALS has no known cause and is described as an idiopathic disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Though its exact cause is unknown, genetic and environmental factors are thought to be of roughly equal importance.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The genetic factors are better understood than the environmental factors; no specific environmental factor has been definitively shown to cause ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] A multi-step liability threshold model for ALS proposes that cellular damage accumulates over time due to genetic factors present at birth and exposure to environmental risks throughout life.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] ALS can strike at any age, but its likelihood increases with age.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Most people who develop ALS are between the ages of 40 and 70, with an average age of 55 at the time of diagnosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] ALS is 20% more common in men than women, but this difference in sex distribution is no longer present in patients with onset after age 70.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] ALS can be classified as either familial or sporadic, depending on whether there is a known family history of the disease and/or whether an ALS-associated genetic mutation has been identified via genetic testing.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Familial ALS is thought to account for 10–15% of cases overall and can include monogenic, oligogenic, and polygenic modes of inheritance.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] There is considerable variation among clinicians on whether to conduct genetic testing in ALS, particularly if there is no discernible family history of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In the past, genetic counseling and testing was only offered to those with obviously familial ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] It is increasingly recognized that cases of sporadic ALS may also be due to disease-causing de novo mutations in *SOD1*, or *C9orf72*, or inherited mutations which were overlooked due to incomplete family history or incomplete penetrance.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] There have been calls in the research community to routinely counsel and test all diagnosed ALS patients for familial ALS, especially due to the availability of genetic medicine (tofersen) for carriers of SOD1 ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] A shortage of genetic counselors and limited clinical capacity to see such at-risk individuals make this challenging in practice, as does the unequal access to genetic testing around the world.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Notably, repeat expansions in the C9orf72 gene account for about 40% of genetic ALS and 25% of genetic FTD, leading to the redefinition of ALS and FTD as lying on a shared disease spectrum.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] ALS genes identified to date explain the cause of about 70% of familial ALS and about 15% of sporadic ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Overall, first-degree relatives of an individual with ALS have a ~1% risk of developing ALS themselves.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] SOD (superoxide dismutase) refers to a group of enzymes that target and reduce the presence of harmful reactive oxygen species (ROS) to protect cells.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Subsequently, SOD enzymes are often critical in ensuring appropriate conditions for neuronal/neural pathway development.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] *SOD1*, a subspecies within the main SOD gene family, is a metalloenzyme characterized by the two main metal groups it contains—Zinc (Zn) and Copper (Cu).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The Cu-Zn superoxide dismutase metabolizes superoxide radicals to oxygen and hydrogen peroxide, defending organisms against oxygen toxicity.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The multi-step hypothesis suggests the disease is caused by some interaction between an individual's genetic risk factors and their cumulative lifetime of exposures to environmental factors, termed their exposome.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The most consistent lifetime exposures associated with developing ALS (other than genetic mutations) include heavy metals (e.g. lead and mercury), chemicals (e.g. pesticides and solvents), electric shock, physical injury (including head injury), and smoking (in men more than women).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Generally, the effect of each exposure is relatively small.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] For instance, an individual's lifetime risk of developing ALS might increase from "1 in 400" without exposure to between "1 in 300" and "1 in 200" if they were exposed to heavy metals.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Some industries are heavily dependent upon the use or exposure to these environmental factors, which may increase employees' susceptibility.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] For example, agricultural tasks may involve as many as 5 such risk factors excluding workers' smoking habits.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] A range of other factors have weaker evidence supporting them and include participation in professional sports, having a lower body mass index, lower educational attainment, manual occupations, military service, exposure to beta-Methylamino-L-alanine (BMAA), and viral infections.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Although some personality traits, such as openness, agreeableness and conscientiousness appear remarkably common among patients with ALS, it remains open whether personality can increase susceptibility to ALS directly.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Instead, genetic factors giving rise to personality might simultaneously predispose people to develop ALS, or the above personality traits might underlie lifestyle choices which are in turn risk factors for ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Many ALS patients have substantially increased expression of endogenous retroviruses (HERVs), which are remnants of infections that may have happened early in human evolution and remained integrated in the human genome.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Similarly, about one in five people with ALS had high levels of retrotransposon activation and dysfunction of TDP-43, a protein which regulates human gene expression and inhibits activation of retroviral genes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Preliminary data suggest that antiviral therapy may be used to treat ALS and related diseases.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Multiple studies have provided evidence suggesting that motor neurons in ALS patients may be susceptible to inflammatory responses driven by autoreactive immune cells.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In 1991, researchers with Baylor College of Medicine found that antibodies could be used to target motor neurons in a mouse model, leading to limb weakness and other symptoms similar to ALS symptoms in humans.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In 2025, researchers at Columbia University Medical School and La Jolla Institute for Immunology published the first study showing inflammatory T cells targeting a specific antigen (vulnerable site) on motor neurons in patients with ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The defining feature of ALS is the death of both upper motor neurons (located in the motor cortex of the brain) and lower motor neurons (located in the brainstem and spinal cord).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In ALS with frontotemporal dementia, neurons throughout the frontal and temporal lobes of the brain die as well.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The pathological hallmark of ALS is the presence of inclusion bodies (abnormal aggregations of protein) known as Bunina bodies in the cytoplasm of motor neurons.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In about 97% of people with ALS, the main component of the inclusion bodies is TDP-43 protein; however, in those with *SOD1* or *FUS* mutations, the main component of the inclusion bodies is SOD1 or FUS protein, respectively.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Prion-like propagation of misfolded proteins from cell to cell may explain why ALS starts in one area and spreads to others.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The glymphatic system may also be involved in the pathogenesis of ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Neurodegeneration in ALS is thought to involve many different cellular and molecular processes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The genes known to be involved in ALS can be grouped into three general categories based on their normal function: protein degradation, the cytoskeleton, and RNA processing.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Mutant SOD1 protein forms intracellular aggregations that inhibit protein degradation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Cytoplasmic aggregations of wild-type (normal) SOD1 protein are common in sporadic ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] It is thought that misfolded mutant SOD1 can cause misfolding and aggregation of wild-type SOD1 in neighboring neurons in a prion-like manner.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Other protein degradation genes that can cause ALS when mutated include *VCP*, *OPTN*, *TBK1*, and *SQSTM1*.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Three genes implicated in ALS that are important for cytoskeletal maintenance and axonal transport include *DCTN1*, *PFN1*, and *TUBA4A*.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Several ALS genes encode RNA-binding proteins.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The first to be discovered was TDP-43 protein, a nuclear protein that aggregates in the cytoplasm of motor neurons in almost all cases of ALS; however, mutations in *TARDBP*, the gene that codes for TDP-43, are a rare cause of ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] *FUS* codes for FUS, another RNA-binding protein with a similar function to TDP-43, which can cause ALS when mutated.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] It is thought that mutations in *TARDBP* and *FUS* increase the binding affinity of the low-complexity domain, causing their respective proteins to aggregate in the cytoplasm.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Once these mutant RNA-binding proteins are misfolded and aggregated, they may be able to misfold normal proteins both within and between cells in a prion-like manner.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] This also leads to decreased levels of RNA-binding protein in the nucleus, which may mean that their target RNA transcripts do not undergo normal processing.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Other RNA metabolism genes associated with ALS include *ANG*, *SETX*, and *MATR3*.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Excitotoxicity, or nerve cell death caused by high levels of intracellular calcium due to excessive stimulation by the excitatory neurotransmitter glutamate, is a mechanism thought to be common to all forms of ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Motor neurons are more sensitive to excitotoxicity than other types of neurons because they have a lower calcium-buffering capacity and a type of glutamate receptor (the AMPA receptor) that is more permeable to calcium.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In ALS, there are decreased levels of excitatory amino acid transporter 2 (EAAT2), which is the main transporter that removes glutamate from the synapse; this leads to increased synaptic glutamate levels and excitotoxicity.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Riluzole, a drug that modestly prolongs survival in ALS, inhibits glutamate release from presynaptic neurons.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] However, it is unclear if this mechanism is responsible for its therapeutic effect.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] No single test can provide a definite diagnosis of ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Instead, the diagnosis of ALS is primarily made based on a physician's clinical assessment after ruling out other diseases.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Physicians often obtain the person's full medical history and conduct neurologic examinations at regular intervals to assess whether signs and symptoms such as muscle weakness, muscle atrophy, hyperreflexia, Babinski's sign, and spasticity are worsening.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Many biomarkers are being studied for the condition, but as of 2023 are not in general medical use.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In the U.S., average time from first symptom to ALS diagnosis confirmation ranges from 11.5 to 15 months.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Even though people with ALS may see 3-4 clinicians prior to referral to an ALS specialist for diagnosis confirmation, the bulk of the diagnostic delay in the U.S. may be while under the care of neurologist(s), particularly non-neuromuscular trained neurologists.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The ALS Association assembled a "Time to Diagnosis" (T2D) workgroup composed of ALS specialists, pharmaceutical industry experts, and people with ALS to focus on developing solutions to reduce diagnostic delays.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] The T2D group developed and published the thinkALS tool, a clinical and referral instrument to increase confidence of early recognition of common ALS clinical features and streamlining referral processes to specialty ALS centers.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Because symptoms of ALS can be similar to those of a wide variety of other diseases or disorders, appropriate tests must be conducted to exclude the possibility of other conditions.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] One of these tests is electromyography (EMG), a special recording technique that detects electrical activity in muscles.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Certain EMG findings can support the diagnosis of ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Another common test measures nerve conduction velocity (NCV).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Specific abnormalities in the NCV results may suggest, for example, that the person has a form of peripheral neuropathy (damage to peripheral nerves) or myopathy (muscle disease) rather than ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] While a magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) is often normal in people with early-stage ALS, it can reveal evidence of other problems that may be causing the symptoms, such as a spinal cord tumor, multiple sclerosis, a herniated disc in the neck, syringomyelia, or cervical spondylosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Based on the person's symptoms and findings from these tests, the physician may order tests on blood and urine samples to eliminate the possibility of other diseases, as well as routine laboratory tests.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] In some cases, for example, if a physician suspects the person may have a myopathy rather than ALS, a muscle biopsy may be performed.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Several infectious diseases can sometimes cause ALS-like symptoms, including human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), human T-lymphotropic virus (HTLV), Lyme disease, and syphilis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Neurological disorders such as multiple sclerosis, post-polio syndrome, multifocal motor neuropathy, CIDP, spinal muscular atrophy, and spinal and bulbar muscular atrophy can also mimic certain aspects of the disease and should be considered.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] ALS must be differentiated from the "ALS mimic syndromes", which are unrelated disorders that may have a similar presentation and clinical features to ALS or its variants.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Because the prognosis of ALS and closely related subtypes of motor neuron disease is generally poor, neurologists may carry out investigations to evaluate and exclude other diagnostic possibilities.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Disorders of the neuromuscular junction, such as myasthenia gravis (MG) and Lambert–Eaton myasthenic syndrome, may also mimic ALS, although this rarely presents diagnostic difficulty over time.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Benign fasciculation syndrome and cramp fasciculation syndrome may also occasionally mimic some of the early symptoms of ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p01] Nonetheless, the absence of other neurological features that develop inexorably with ALS means that, over time, the distinction will not present any difficulty to the experienced neurologist; where doubt remains, EMG may be helpful.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Management focuses on treating symptoms and providing supportive care to improve quality of life and prolong survival.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] This care is best provided by multidisciplinary teams of healthcare professionals; attending a multidisciplinary ALS clinic is associated with longer survival, fewer hospitalizations, and improved quality of life.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Non-invasive ventilation (NIV) is the main treatment for respiratory failure in ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In people with normal bulbar function, it prolongs survival by at least several months and improves the quality of life.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] One study found that NIV is ineffective for people with poor bulbar function while another suggested that it may provide a modest survival benefit.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Invasive ventilation is an option for people with advanced ALS when NIV is not enough to manage their symptoms.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Though invasive ventilation prolongs survival, disease progression, and functional decline continue.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] It may decrease the quality of life of people with ALS or their caregivers.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Invasive ventilation is more commonly used in Japan than in North America or Europe.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Physical therapy can promote functional independence through aerobic, range of motion, and stretching exercises.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Occupational therapy can assist with activities of daily living through adaptive equipment.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Speech therapy can assist people with ALS who have difficulty speaking.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Preventing weight loss and malnutrition in people with ALS improves both survival and quality of life.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Initially, difficulty swallowing (dysphagia) can be managed by dietary changes and swallowing techniques.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] A feeding tube should be considered if someone with ALS loses 5% or more of their body weight or if they cannot safely swallow food and water.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The feeding tube is usually inserted by percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy (PEG).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] There is weak evidence that PEG tubes improve survival.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] PEG insertion is usually performed with the intent of improving quality of life.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Palliative care should begin shortly after someone is diagnosed with ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Discussion of end-of-life issues gives people with ALS time to reflect on their preferences for end-of-life care and can help avoid unwanted interventions or procedures.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Hospice care can improve symptom management at the end of life and increase the likelihood of a peaceful death.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In the final days of life, opioids can be used to treat pain and dyspnea, while benzodiazepines can be used to treat anxiety.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Riluzole has been found to modestly prolong survival by about 2–3 months.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] It may have a greater survival benefit for those with bulbar-onset ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] It may work by decreasing release of the excitatory neurotransmitter glutamate from pre-synaptic neurons.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The most common side effects are nausea and a lack of energy (asthenia).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] People with ALS should begin treatment with riluzole as soon as possible following their diagnosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Riluzole is available as a tablet, liquid, or dissolvable oral film.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Edaravone has been shown to modestly slow the decline in function in a small group of people with early-stage ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] It may work by protecting motor neurons from oxidative stress.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The most common side effects are bruising and gait disturbance.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Edaravone is available as an intravenous infusion or as an oral suspension.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Tofersen (Qalsody) is an antisense oligonucleotide that was approved for medical use in the United States in April 2023 for the treatment of SOD1-associated ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In a study of 108 patients with SOD1-associated ALS there was a non-significant trend towards a slowing of progression, as well as a significant reduction in neurofilament light chain, a putative ALS biomarker thought to indicate neuronal damage.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] A follow-up study and open-label extension suggested that earlier treatment initiation had a beneficial effect on slowing disease progression.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Tofersen is available as an intrathecal injection into the lumbar cistern at the base of the spine.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Several gene-targeted therapies are currently under clinical investigation for ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Ulefnersen (ION363), an investigational drug designed to suppress the production of toxic mutant FUS protein, is the furthest along and is completing a global Phase 3 trial for FUS-associated ALS in the second half of 2026.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Therapies addressing UNC13A mis-splicing are in earlier stages of development, with candidates like QRL-201 showing encouraging safety and biomarker trends in Phase 1/2 proof-of-concept trials ahead of planned Phase 3 evaluation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Other medications may be used to help reduce fatigue, ease muscle cramps, control spasticity, and reduce excess saliva and phlegm.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Gabapentin, pregabalin, and tricyclic antidepressants (e.g., amitriptyline) can be used for neuropathic pain, while nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), acetaminophen, and opioids can be used for nociceptive pain.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Depression can be treated with selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) or tricyclic antidepressants, while benzodiazepines can be used for anxiety.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] There are no medications to treat cognitive impairment/frontotemporal dementia (FTD); however, SSRIs and antipsychotics can help treat some of the symptoms of FTD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Pseudobulbar affect can be treated with Nuedexta (dextromethorphan/quinidine), though this relatively new compound is not available in every country.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Baclofen and tizanidine are the most commonly used oral drugs for treating spasticity; an intrathecal baclofen pump can be used for severe spasticity, and mexiletine is safe and effective for treating cramps.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Atropine, scopolamine, amitriptyline, or glycopyrrolate may be prescribed when people with ALS begin having trouble swallowing their saliva (sialorrhea).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Non-invasive ventilation (NIV) is the primary treatment for respiratory failure in ALS and was the first treatment shown to improve both survival and quality of life.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] NIV uses a face or nasal mask connected to a ventilator that provides intermittent positive pressure to support breathing.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] They may also take self-paced breaths using a mouthpiece.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Continuous positive pressure is not recommended for people with ALS because it makes breathing more difficult.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Initially, NIV is used only at night because the first sign of respiratory failure is decreased gas exchange (hypoventilation) during sleep; symptoms associated with this nocturnal hypoventilation include interrupted sleep, anxiety, morning headaches, and daytime fatigue.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] As the disease progresses, people with ALS develop shortness of breath when lying down, during physical activity or talking, and eventually at rest.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Other symptoms include poor concentration, poor memory, confusion, respiratory tract infections, and a weak cough.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Respiratory failure is the most common cause of death in ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] It is important to monitor the respiratory function of people with ALS every three months because beginning NIV soon after the start of respiratory symptoms is associated with increased survival.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] This involves asking the person with ALS if they have any respiratory symptoms and measuring their respiratory function.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The most commonly used measurement is upright forced vital capacity (FVC), but it is a poor detector of early respiratory failure and is not a good choice for those with bulbar symptoms, as they have difficulty maintaining a tight seal around the mouthpiece.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Measuring FVC while the person is lying on their back (supine FVC) is a more accurate measure of diaphragm weakness than upright FVC.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Sniff nasal inspiratory pressure (SNIP) is a rapid, convenient test of diaphragm strength that is not affected by bulbar muscle weakness.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] If someone with ALS has signs and symptoms of respiratory failure, they should undergo daytime blood gas analysis to look for hypoxemia (low oxygen in the blood) and hypercapnia (too much carbon dioxide in the blood).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] If their daytime blood gas analysis is normal, they should then have nocturnal pulse oximetry to look for hypoxemia during sleep.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Non-invasive ventilation prolongs survival longer than riluzole.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] A 2006 randomized controlled trial found that NIV prolongs survival by about 48 days and improves the quality of life; however, it also found that some people with ALS benefit more from this intervention than others.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] For those with normal or only moderately impaired bulbar function, NIV prolongs survival by about seven months and significantly improves the quality of life.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] For those with poor bulbar function, NIV neither prolongs survival nor improves the quality of life, though it does improve some sleep-related symptoms.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Despite the clear benefits of NIV, about 25–30% of all people with ALS are unable to tolerate it, especially those with cognitive impairment or bulbar dysfunction.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Results from a large 2015 cohort study suggest that NIV may prolong survival in those with bulbar weakness, so NIV should be offered to all people with ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Invasive ventilation bypasses the nose and mouth (the upper airways) by making a cut in the trachea (tracheostomy) and inserting a tube connected to a ventilator.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] It is an option for people with advanced ALS whose respiratory symptoms are poorly managed despite continuous NIV use.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] While invasive ventilation prolongs survival, especially for those younger than 60, it does not treat the underlying neurodegenerative process.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The person with ALS will continue to lose motor function, making communication increasingly difficult and sometimes leading to locked-in syndrome, in which they are completely paralyzed except for their eye muscles.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] About half of the people with ALS who choose to undergo invasive ventilation report a decrease in their quality of life, but most still consider it to be satisfactory.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] However, invasive ventilation imposes a heavy burden on caregivers and may decrease their quality of life.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Attitudes toward invasive ventilation vary from country to country; about 30% of people with ALS in Japan choose invasive ventilation, versus less than 5% in North America and Europe.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Physical therapy plays a large role in rehabilitation for individuals with ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Specifically, physical, occupational, and speech therapists can set goals and promote benefits for individuals with ALS by delaying loss of strength, maintaining endurance, limiting pain, improving speech and swallowing, preventing complications, and promoting functional independence.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Occupational therapy and special equipment such as assistive technology can also enhance people's independence and safety throughout ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Gentle, low-impact aerobic exercise such as performing activities of daily living, walking, swimming, and stationary bicycling can strengthen unaffected muscles, improve cardiovascular health, and help people fight fatigue and depression.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Range of motion and stretching exercises can help prevent painful spasticity and shortening (contracture) of muscles.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Physical and occupational therapists can recommend exercises that provide these benefits without overworking muscles because muscle exhaustion can lead to a worsening of symptoms associated with ALS, rather than providing help to people with ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] They can suggest devices such as ramps, braces, walkers, bathroom equipment (shower chairs, toilet risers, etc.), and wheelchairs that help people remain mobile.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Occupational therapists can provide or recommend equipment and adaptations to enable people with ALS to retain as much safety and independence in activities of daily living as possible.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Since respiratory insufficiency is the primary cause of mortality, physical therapists can help improve respiratory outcomes in people with ALS by implementing pulmonary physical therapy.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] This includes inspiratory muscle training, lung volume recruitment training, and manual assisted cough therapy aimed at increasing respiratory muscle strength as well as increasing survival rates.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] People with ALS who have difficulty speaking or swallowing may benefit from working with a speech-language pathologist.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] These health professionals can teach people adaptive strategies, such as techniques to help them speak louder and more clearly.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Weight loss in ALS is often caused by muscle wasting and increased resting energy expenditure.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Weight loss may also be secondary to reduced food intake since dysphagia develops in about 85% of people with ALS at some point throughout their disease course.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Therefore, regular periodic assessment of the weight and swallowing ability in people with ALS is very important.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Dysphagia is often initially managed via dietary changes and modified swallowing techniques.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] People with ALS are often instructed to avoid dry or chewy foods in their diet and instead have meals that are soft, moist, and easy to swallow.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Switching to thick liquids (like fruit nectar or smoothies) or adding thickeners (to thin fluids like water and coffee) may also help people facing difficulty swallowing liquids.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] There is tentative evidence that high-calorie diets with a focus on "good fats" rather than simple carbohydrates, may prevent further weight loss and improve survival, but more research is still needed.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] This can take the form of a gastrostomy tube, in which a tube is placed through the wall of the abdomen into the stomach, or (less commonly) a nasogastric tube, in which a tube is placed through the nose and down the esophagus into the stomach.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] A gastrostomy tube is more appropriate for long-term use than a nasogastric tube, which is uncomfortable and can cause esophageal ulcers.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The feeding tube is usually placed by a radiologically inserted gastrostomy (RIG) or a percutaneous endoscopic gastrostomy procedure (PEG), depending on the hospital involved and the patient's medical history.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Accordingly, PEG tubes are offered with the intent of improving the person's quality of life as well as survival, by sustaining nutrition, hydration status, and medication intake.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Palliative care, which relieves symptoms and improves the quality of life without treating the underlying disease, should begin shortly after someone is diagnosed with ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Early discussion of end-of-life issues gives people with ALS time to reflect on their preferences for end-of-life care and can help avoid unwanted interventions or procedures.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Once they have been fully informed about all aspects of various life-prolonging measures, they can fill out advance directives indicating their attitude toward noninvasive ventilation, invasive ventilation, and feeding tubes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Late in the disease course, difficulty speaking due to muscle weakness (dysarthria) and cognitive dysfunction may impair their ability to communicate their wishes regarding care.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Continued failure to solicit the preferences of the person with ALS may lead to unplanned and potentially unwanted emergency interventions, such as invasive ventilation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] If people with ALS or their family members are reluctant to discuss end-of-life issues, it may be useful to use the introduction of gastrostomy or noninvasive ventilation as an opportunity to bring up the subject.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Hospice care, or palliative care at the end of life, is especially important in ALS because it helps to optimize the management of symptoms and increases the likelihood of a peaceful death.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] It is unclear exactly when the end-of-life phase begins in ALS, but it is associated with significant difficulty moving, communicating, and, in some cases, thinking.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Although many people with ALS fear choking to death (suffocating), they can be reassured that this occurs rarely, less than 1% of the time.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Most patients die at home, and in the final days of life, opioids can be used to treat pain and dyspnea, while benzodiazepines can be used to treat anxiety.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] ALS is the most common motor neuron disease in adults and the third most common neurodegenerative disease after Alzheimer's disease and Parkinson's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Worldwide, the number of people who develop ALS yearly is estimated to be 1.9 people per 100,000 per year, while the number of people who have ALS at any given time is estimated to be about 4.5 people per 100,000.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In Europe, the number of new cases a year is about 2.6 people per 100,000, while the number affected is 7–9 people per 100,000.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The lifetime risk of developing ALS is 1:350 for European men and 1:400 for European women.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Men have a higher risk mainly because spinal-onset ALS is more common in men than women.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The number of people with ALS in the United States in 2015 was 5.2 people per 100,000, and was higher in whites, males, and people over 60 years old.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The number of new cases is about 0.8 people per 100,000 per year in East Asia and about 0.7 people per 100,000 per year in South Asia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] About 80% of ALS epidemiology studies have been conducted in Europe and the United States, mostly in people of northern European descent.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] There is not enough information to determine the rates of ALS in much of the world, including Africa, parts of Asia, India, Russia, and South America.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] There are several geographic clusters in the Western Pacific where the prevalence of ALS was reported to be 50–100 times higher than in the rest of the world, including Guam, the Kii Peninsula of Japan, and Western New Guinea.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The incidence in these areas has decreased since the 1960s; the cause remains unknown.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] People of all races and ethnic backgrounds may be affected by ALS, but it is more common in whites than in Africans, Asians, or Hispanics.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In the United States in 2015, the prevalence of ALS in whites was 5.4 people per 100,000, while the prevalence in African Americans was 2.3 people per 100,000.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The Midwest had the highest prevalence of the four U.S.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Census regions, with 5.5 people per 100,000, followed by the Northeast (5.1), the South (4.7), and the West (4.4).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The Midwest and Northeast likely had a higher prevalence of ALS because they have a higher proportion of whites than the South and West.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Ethnically mixed populations may be at a lower risk of developing ALS; a study in Cuba found that people of mixed ancestry were less likely to die from ALS than whites or blacks.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] There are also differences in the genetics of ALS between different ethnic groups; the most common ALS gene in Europe is *C9orf72*, followed by *SOD1*, *TARDBP*, and *FUS*, while the most common ALS gene in Asia is *SOD1*, followed by *FUS*, *C9orf72*, and *TARDBP*.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] ALS can affect people at any age, but the peak incidence is between 50 and 75 years and decreases dramatically after 80 years.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The reason for the decreased incidence in the elderly is unclear.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] One thought is that people who survive into their 80s may not be genetically susceptible to developing ALS; alternatively, ALS in the elderly might go undiagnosed because of comorbidities (other diseases they have), difficulty seeing a neurologist, or dying quickly from an aggressive form of ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In the United States in 2015, the lowest prevalence was in the 18–39 age group, while the highest prevalence was in the 70–79 age group.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Sporadic ALS usually starts around the ages of 58 to 63 years, while genetic ALS starts earlier, usually around 47 to 52 years.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The number of ALS cases worldwide is projected to increase from 222,801 in 2015 to 376,674 in 2040, an increase of 69%.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] This will largely be due to the aging of the world's population, especially in developing countries.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In 1850, François-Amilcar Aran was the first to describe a disorder he named "progressive muscular atrophy", a form of ALS in which only the lower motor neurons are affected.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In 1869, the connection between the symptoms and the underlying neurological problems was first described by Jean-Martin Charcot, who initially introduced the term *amyotrophic lateral sclerosis* in his 1874 paper.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Flail arm syndrome, a regional variant of ALS, was first described by Alfred Vulpian in 1886.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Flail leg syndrome, another regional variant of ALS, was first described by Pierre Marie and his student Patrikios in 1918.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In the 1950s, electrodiagnostic testing (EMG) and nerve conduction velocity (NCV) testing began to be used to evaluate clinically suspected ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Lambert published the first EMG/NCS diagnostic criteria for ALS, consisting of four findings he considered to strongly support the diagnosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Since then, several diagnostic criteria have been developed, which are mostly in use for research purposes for inclusion/exclusion criteria, and to stratify patients for analysis in trials.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Research diagnostic criteria for ALS include the "El Escorial" in 1994, revised in 1998.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In 2006, the "Awaji" criteria proposed using EMG and NCV tests to help diagnose ALS earlier, and most recently, the "Gold Coast" criteria in 2019 simplified diagnosis, included cognitive change, and no longer required multiple regions to be affected.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] ALS is sometimes referred to as *Charcot's disease* (not to be confused with Charcot–Marie–Tooth disease or Charcot joint disease), because Jean-Martin Charcot was the first to connect the clinical symptoms with the pathology seen at autopsy.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] The British neurologist Russell Brain coined the term *motor neuron disease* in 1933 to reflect his belief that ALS, progressive bulbar palsy, and progressive muscular atrophy were all different forms of the same disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In some countries, especially the United States, ALS is called *Lou Gehrig's disease* after the American baseball player Lou Gehrig, who was diagnosed with ALS in 1939.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In the United States and continental Europe, the term *ALS* (as well as *Lou Gehrig's disease* in the U.S.) refers to all forms of the disease, including "classical" ALS, progressive bulbar palsy, progressive muscular atrophy, and primary lateral sclerosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In the United Kingdom and Australia, the term *motor neuron disease* refers to all forms of the disease, while *ALS* only refers to "classical" ALS, meaning the form with both upper and lower motor neuron involvement.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In addition to the baseball player Lou Gehrig, several notable individuals have or have had ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Theoretical physicist Stephen Hawking, who notably lived longer than any other known person with the condition, was the subject of the critically acclaimed biopic *The Theory of Everything*.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] American sociology professor and ALS patient Morrie Schwartz was the subject of the memoir *Tuesdays with Morrie* and the film of the same name.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] In August 2014, the "Ice Bucket Challenge" to raise money for ALS research went viral online.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Participants filmed themselves filling a bucket full of ice water and pouring it onto themselves; they then nominated other individuals to do the same.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/als-p02] Many participants donated to ALS research at the ALS Association, the ALS Therapy Development Institute, ALS Society of Canada, or Motor Neurone Disease Association in the UK.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The causes of Alzheimer's disease remain poorly understood.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] There are many environmental and genetic risk factors associated with its development.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The strongest genetic risk factor is from an allele of apolipoprotein E, a protein involved in the metabolism of fats in mammals.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Other risk factors include a history of head injury, clinical depression, and high blood pressure.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The progression of the disease is largely characterised by the accumulation of malformed protein deposits in the cerebral cortex, called amyloid plaques and neurofibrillary tangles.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] These misfolded protein aggregates interfere with normal cell function, and over time lead to irreversible degeneration of neurons and loss of synaptic connections in the brain.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] A probable diagnosis is based on the history of the illness and cognitive testing, with medical imaging and blood tests to rule out other possible causes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Initial symptoms are often mistaken for normal brain aging.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Examination of brain tissue at postmortem used to be the only way to definitively diagnose Alzheimer's, but neuroimaging techniques and fluid biomarkers have made diagnosis in vivo possible.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] No known treatments can stop or reverse its progression, though some may temporarily improve symptoms.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] A healthy diet, physical activity, and social engagement are generally beneficial in aging, and may help in reducing the risk of cognitive decline and Alzheimer's.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Affected people become increasingly reliant on others for assistance, often placing a burden on caregivers.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The pressures can include social, psychological, physical, and economic elements.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Exercise programs may be beneficial with respect to activities of daily living and can potentially improve outcomes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Behavioral problems or psychosis due to dementia are sometimes treated with antipsychotics, but this has an increased risk of early death.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] As of 2020, there were approximately 50 million people worldwide with Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] It most often begins in people over 65 years of age, although up to 10% of cases are early-onset impacting those in their 30s to mid-60s.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] It affects about 6% of people 65 years and older, and women more often than men.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The disease is named after German psychiatrist and pathologist Alois Alzheimer, who first described it in 1906.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Alzheimer's financial burden on society is large, with an estimated global annual cost of US$1 trillion.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Alzheimer's and related dementias are ranked as the seventh leading cause of death worldwide.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Given the widespread impacts of Alzheimer's disease, both basic-science and health funders in many countries support Alzheimer's research at large scales.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] For example, the US National Institutes of Health program for Alzheimer's research, the National Plan to Address Alzheimer's Disease, has a budget of US$3.98 billion for fiscal year 2026.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In the European Union, the 2020 Horizon Europe research programme awarded over €570 million for dementia-related projects.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The course of Alzheimer's is generally described in three stages, with a progressive pattern of cognitive and functional impairment.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The three stages are described as early or mild, middle or moderate, and late or severe.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The disease is known to target the hippocampus, which is associated with memory, and this is responsible for the first symptoms of memory impairment.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] As the disease progresses, so does the degree of memory impairment.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The first symptoms are often mistakenly attributed to aging or stress.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Detailed neuropsychological testing can reveal mild cognitive difficulties up to eight years before a person fulfills the clinical criteria for diagnosis of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] These early symptoms can affect the most complex activities of daily living.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The most noticeable deficit is short term memory loss, which shows up as difficulty in remembering recently learned facts and inability to acquire new information.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Subtle problems with the executive functions of attentiveness, planning, flexibility, and abstract thinking, or impairments in semantic memory (memory of meanings and concept relationships) can also be symptomatic of the early stages of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Apathy and depression can be seen at this stage, with apathy remaining as the most persistent symptom throughout the course of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] People with objective signs of cognitive impairment, but not more severe symptoms, may be diagnosed with mild cognitive impairment (MCI).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] If memory loss is the predominant symptom of MCI, it is termed amnestic MCI and is frequently seen as a prodromal or early stage of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Amnestic MCI has a greater than 90% likelihood of being associated with Alzheimer's.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In people with Alzheimer's disease, the increasing impairment of learning and memory eventually leads to a definitive diagnosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In a small percentage, difficulties with language, executive functions, perception (agnosia), or execution of movements (apraxia) are more prominent than memory problems.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Alzheimer's disease does not affect all memory capacities equally.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Older memories of the person's life (episodic memory), facts learned (semantic memory), and implicit memory (the memory of the body on how to do things, such as using a fork to eat or how to drink from a glass) are affected to a lesser degree than new facts or memories.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Language problems are mainly characterised by a shrinking vocabulary and decreased word fluency, leading to a general impoverishment of oral and written language.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In this stage, the person with Alzheimer's is usually capable of communicating basic ideas adequately.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] While performing fine motor tasks such as writing, drawing, or dressing, certain movement coordination and planning difficulties (apraxia) may be present; however, they are commonly unnoticed.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] As the disease progresses, people with Alzheimer's disease can often continue to perform many tasks independently; however, they may need assistance or supervision with the most cognitively demanding activities.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Progressive deterioration eventually hinders independence, with subjects being unable to perform the most common activities of daily living.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Speech difficulties become evident due to an inability to recall vocabulary, which leads to frequent incorrect word substitutions (paraphasias).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Reading and writing skills are also progressively lost.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Complex motor sequences become less coordinated as time passes and Alzheimer's disease progresses, so the risk of falling increases.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] During this phase, memory problems worsen, and the person may fail to recognise close relatives.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Long-term memory, which was previously intact, becomes impaired.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Behavioral and neuropsychiatric changes become more prevalent.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Common manifestations are wandering, irritability and emotional lability, leading to crying, outbursts of unpremeditated aggression, or resistance to caregiving.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Approximately 30% of people with Alzheimer's disease develop illusionary misidentifications and other delusional symptoms.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Subjects also lose insight of their disease process and limitations (anosognosia).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] These symptoms create stress for relatives and caregivers, which can be reduced by moving the person from home care to other long-term care facilities.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] During the final stage, known as the late-stage or severe stage, there is complete dependence on caregivers.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Language is reduced to simple phrases or even single words, eventually leading to complete loss of speech.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Despite the loss of verbal language abilities, people can often understand and return emotional signals.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Although aggressiveness can still be present, extreme apathy and exhaustion are much more common symptoms.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] People with Alzheimer's disease will ultimately not be able to perform even the simplest tasks independently; muscle mass and mobility deteriorate to the point where they are bedridden and unable to feed themselves.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The cause of death is usually an external factor, such as infection of pressure ulcers or pneumonia, not the disease itself.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In some cases, there is a paradoxical lucidity immediately before death, where there is an unexpected recovery of mental clarity.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] This altered protein clearance ability is age-related, regulated by brain cholesterol, and associated with other neurodegenerative diseases.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Deterministic causes for most Alzheimer's cases are still mostly unknown, except for 1–2% of cases where deterministic genetic differences have been identified.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Predisposing causes (also known as "risk factors") such as hearing impairment and smoking are increasingly documented.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Several unifying hypotheses attempt to explain underlying causes; the most predominant are the amyloid beta (Aβ) hypothesis, and the tau hypothesis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Late-onset Alzheimer's is about 70% heritable.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Most cases of Alzheimer's are not familial, and so they are termed sporadic Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Of the cases of sporadic Alzheimer's disease, most are classified as late onset where they are developed after the age of 65 years.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The strongest genetic risk factor for sporadic Alzheimer's disease is APOEε4.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] APOEε4 is one of the three major alleles of apolipoprotein E (APOE).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] APOE plays a major role in lipid-binding proteins in lipoprotein particles and the ε4 allele disrupts this function.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Between 40% and 80% of people with Alzheimer's disease possess at least one APOEε4 allele.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The APOEε4 allele increases the risk of the disease by three times in heterozygotes and by 15 times in homozygotes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Like many human diseases, environmental effects and genetic modifiers result in incomplete penetrance.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] For example, Nigerian Yoruba people do not show the relationship between the dose of APOEε4 and incidence or age-of-onset for Alzheimer's disease seen in other human populations.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Only 1–2% of Alzheimer's cases are inherited due to autosomal dominant mutations, as Alzheimer's disease is substantially polygenic.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] When autosomal dominant variants cause the disease, it is known as early-onset familial Alzheimer's disease, which is rarer and tends to progress more rapidly.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Less than 5% of sporadic Alzheimer's disease have an earlier onset, and early-onset Alzheimer's is about 90% heritable.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Familial Alzheimer's disease usually implies two or more persons affected in one or more generations.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Early onset familial Alzheimer's disease can be attributed to mutations in one of three genes: those encoding amyloid-beta precursor protein (APP) and presenilins PSEN1 and PSEN2.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Most mutations in the APP and presenilin genes increase the production of a small protein called amyloid beta (Aβ)42, which is the main component of amyloid plaques.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Some of the mutations merely alter the ratio between Aβ42 and the other major forms—particularly Aβ40—without increasing total Aβ levels in the brain.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Two other genes associated with autosomal dominant Alzheimer's disease are ABCA7 and SORL1.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Alleles in the TREM2 gene have been associated with a three to five times higher risk of developing Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] A Japanese pedigree of familial Alzheimer's disease was found to be associated with a deletion mutation of codon 693 of APP.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] This mutation and its association with Alzheimer's disease was first reported in 2008, and is known as the Osaka mutation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Only homozygotes with this mutation have an increased risk of developing Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] This mutation accelerates Aβ oligomerization, but the proteins do not form the amyloid fibrils that aggregate into amyloid plaques, suggesting that Aβ oligomerization rather than the fibrils may be the cause of this disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Mice expressing this mutation have all the usual pathologies of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Two abnormal proteins define the pathology of Alzheimer's disease: amyloid beta protein (Aβ) in amyloid plaques and tau protein in neurofibrillary tangles.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] These proteins share two features that promote their ability to cause disease: They both become abnormal by misfolding, that is, by assuming a shape that is rich in beta sheets; and they proliferate in the brain by the prion-like mechanism of seeded protein aggregation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The presence of these abnormal proteins in Alzheimer's disease has spawned two hypotheses of the proteopathic origin of the disease: The amyloid (or Aβ) hypothesis, and the tau hypothesis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The amyloid hypothesis, also known as the "amyloid cascade hypothesis" or "Aβ cascade hypothesis", holds that the accumulation of misfolded Aβ in the brain is the fundamental cause of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In the amyloid cascade, the buildup of abnormal Aβ leads to tauopathy and eventually the complex degenerative changes of advanced Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Abnormal Aβ is thought to damage the brain by directly interacting with cells, and/or indirectly, for example by causing oxidative stress and neuroinflammation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The amyloid hypothesis is supported by evidence from genetics and biomarkers.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] All autosomal dominant genetic causes of Alzheimer's disease affect either the amyloid precursor protein (APP) on chromosome 21 or the enzymes that generate Aβ, known as presenilin 1 and presenilin 2.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In addition, people with trisomy 21 (Down syndrome), most of whom have an extra copy of the gene for APP, almost universally develop the symptoms and neuropathology of Alzheimer's disease by 40 years of age.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Conversely, people with a rare mutation in the APP gene that reduces the production of Aβ and its tendency to aggregate are protected against Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Additionally, a major genetic risk factor for Alzheimer's disease is a specific isoform of apolipoprotein E, APOE4.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Of the three major isoforms (APOE2, APOE3 and APOE4), APOE4 is linked to the least efficient removal of Aβ by astrocytes, which promotes the buildup of Aβ in the brain.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The most efficient clearance of Aβ is achieved by cells bearing the APOE2 isoform, which protects against Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Evidence from biomarkers such as imaging of protein deposits in the brain and measurement of brain-derived substances in cerebrospinal fluid and blood implicates abnormalities of Aβ as the earliest and most robust disease-specific change in Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The tau hypothesis proposes that abnormalities of the tau protein initiate the disease cascade, at least in cases of idiopathic Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The tau hypothesis is supported by the histopathological findings of Heiko Braak and colleagues that tauopathy can be detected in certain neurons before Aβ plaques are evident.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Specifically, Alzheimer's starts with the hyperphosphorylation of tau in specific vulnerable neuronal populations such as the locus coeruleus and projection neurons of the association cortex.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] There is agreement in the research community that tau contributes strongly to dementia in Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Tauopathy occurs in over 30 diseases in addition to Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In addition, mutations of the gene for tau (MAPT) cause neurodegenerative disorders known as primary tauopathies, but these diseases occur in the absence of Aβ proteopathy.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Current evidence thus favors abnormal Aβ as the prime mover of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] However, the Aβ hypothesis and tau hypothesis are not mutually exclusive, in that abnormalities of Aβ initiate the disease and tauopathy is required for its complete expression.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Because women have a higher incidence of AD than men, it has been thought that estrogen deficiency during menopause is a risk factor.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In a 2025 analysis of the Canadian Longitudinal Study on Aging, earlier age at menopause was linked with lower cognitive performance.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The possibility that infectious agents cause Alzheimer's disease has been considered since the early 20th century, when Oskar Fischer likened amyloid plaques to small masses (called 'Drusen') of a microbe called actinomyces.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Since then, at least 15 different agents, including bacteria, viruses, fungi and protozoa, have been proposed to cause Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] No definitive evidence has been presented that a specific infectious agent is necessary and sufficient to cause Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] However, it is possible that microbial infections might act as risk factors for the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] For example, human herpes viruses such as HSV-1, HHV-6, and HHV-7 have been linked to the risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In addition, some pathogens have been reported to seed Aβ deposition in the brain, and aggregated Aβ has antimicrobial properties, suggesting that Aβ plaques might form when brain cells generate Aβ to fight infection.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Researchers caution that brain infections can cause dementia by mechanisms unrelated to Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] DNA damage accumulates in affected brains; reactive oxygen species may be the major source of this DNA damage.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The cholinergic hypothesis proposes that the loss of neurons in the basal forebrain, which produce the neurotransmitter acetylcholine, is a key event in the pathogenesis of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] These cells supply acetylcholine to synapses in the limbic system and cerebral cortex.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The cholinergic hypothesis led to the development of drugs that increase acetylcholine in the brains of Alzheimer patients.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The efficacy of these agents is limited, probably because many other neurotransmitter systems degenerate in Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Sleep disturbances are seen as a possible risk factor for inflammation in Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Sleep disruption was previously only seen as a consequence of Alzheimer's disease, but as of 2020, accumulating evidence suggests that this relationship may be bidirectional.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Systemic markers of the innate immune system are risk factors for late-onset Alzheimer's disease, and misfolded Aβ and tau proteins both are associated with oxidative stress and neuroinflammation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Chronic inflammation also is a feature of other neurodegenerative diseases, including Parkinson's disease, and ALS.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The cellular homeostasis of biometals such as ionic copper, iron, and zinc is disrupted in Alzheimer's disease, though it remains unclear whether this is produced by or causes the changes in proteins.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Smoking is a significant Alzheimer's disease risk factor.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Exposure to air pollution may be a contributing factor to the development of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Likewise the hypothesis is, that as infants go through states of cognitive development, people with Alzheimer's disease go through the reverse process of progressive cognitive impairment.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] According to one theory, dysfunction of oligodendrocytes and their associated myelin during aging contributes to axon damage, which in turn generates amyloid production and tau hyperphosphorylation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Comorbidities between the demyelinating disease, multiple sclerosis, and Alzheimer's disease have been reported.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The association with celiac disease is unclear, with a 2019 study finding no increase in dementia overall in those with celiac disease, while a 2018 review found an association with several types of dementia, including Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Some studies have reported a potential link between infection with certain viruses and developing Alzheimer's disease later in life, such as COVID-19 or Herpes simplex virus 1 (HSV-1).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Some researchers have proposed that Alzheimer's disease is type 3 diabetes because of a number of correspondences with both type 1 and type 2 diabetes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The gross (macroscopic) appearance of the brain in Alzheimer's disease is variable.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In many cases the cortical sulci are widened and the gyri are shrunken, but the degree of cortical atrophy varies.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] It can sometimes be difficult to discern, particularly in the very elderly.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The areas most affected by atrophy are the medial temporal lobe including the hippocampal formation, the amygdala, the frontal lobe and the parietal lobe; the occipital lobe is relatively unaffected by atrophy.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The volume of the ventricles increases in parallel with cortical shrinkage.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Studies using MRI and PET have documented reductions in the size of specific brain regions in people with Alzheimer's disease as they progress from mild cognitive impairment to Alzheimer's disease, and in comparison with similar images from healthy older adults.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] These macroscopic changes in the brain are not specific to Alzheimer's and can occur in other disorders and to some extent in normal aging.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] At the microscopic level, the defining histopathologic characteristics of Alzheimer's disease are abundant amyloid plaques and neurofibrillary tangles in certain brain regions.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Both of these abnormalities are clearly visible by microscopy, and amyloid imaging.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In the early stages of disease, tangles are present mainly in the medial temporal lobe and plaques are present mainly in the neocortex, but as the disease progresses the lesions proliferate throughout much of the brain.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Although it was once thought that Alzheimer's disease can occur without neurofibrillary tangles in the neocortex, newer methods have shown that dementia in these cases can be linked to a comorbid condition, often Lewy body disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Aβ plaques are dense, mostly insoluble deposits of amyloid beta peptide and cellular material outside and around neurons.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Neurofibrillary tangles are aggregates of the microtubule-associated protein tau which has become hyperphosphorylated and accumulates inside neurons.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Although many older individuals develop some plaques and tangles as a consequence of aging, the brains of people with Alzheimer's disease have a greater number of them in specific brain regions.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In addition to plaques and tangles, other neuropathological changes contribute to the clinicopathological features of advanced Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] These include cerebral Aβ-amyloid angiopathy (CAA), inflammation, and the loss of neurons and synapses.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The disappearance of neurons and their synapses is a particularly prominent correlate of dementia, although not all cells are affected equally.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Selective vulnerability - that is, why certain neurons and synapses are affected, and others spared - is an important unanswered question.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In more than half of the cases examined neuropathologically, and especially in very old people, the pathology of Alzheimer's disease is accompanied by lesions that are characteristic of other brain disorders.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The most common of these comorbid conditions are vascular disease, Lewy body disease, and TDP-43 proteinopathy.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] This mixed pathology can complicate both diagnosis and the evaluation of clinical trials, which often target only one of several potential contributors to dementia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Alzheimer's disease has been identified as a protein misfolding disease, a proteopathy, caused by the accumulation of abnormally folded Aβ protein into amyloid plaques, and tau protein into neurofibrillary tangles in the brain.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Plaques are made up of small peptides, 39–43 amino acids in length, called Aβ.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Aβ is a fragment derived from the larger Aβ precursor protein (APP), a transmembrane protein that penetrates the cell's membrane.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] APP is critical to neuronal growth, survival, and post-injury repair.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In Alzheimer's disease, the enzymes gamma secretase and beta secretase act together in a proteolytic process that divides APP into smaller fragments.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] One of these fragments is Aβ, which misfolds and self-assembles into fibrils; these fibrils form clumps that deposit outside neurons in dense formations known as Aβ plaques.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Excitatory neurons are known to be major producers of Aβ that contribute to extracellular plaque deposition.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Enzymes act on the amyloid-beta precursor protein and cut it into fragments.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The beta-amyloid fragment is crucial in the formation of amyloid plaques in Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Alzheimer's disease is also considered a tauopathy due to the abnormal aggregation of the tau protein within cells.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Every neuron has a cytoskeleton, an internal support structure partly made up of organelles called microtubules.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] These microtubules act like tracks, guiding nutrients and molecules from the body of the cell to the ends of the axon and back.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The tau protein stabilises the microtubules when phosphorylated, and it is therefore called a microtubule-associated protein.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In Alzheimer's disease, tau undergoes chemical changes, becoming hyperphosphorylated; it then begins to pair with other threads, creating neurofibrillary tangles and disintegrating the neuron's transport system.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Pathogenic tau can also cause neuronal death through transposable element dysregulation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Necroptosis has also been reported as a mechanism of cell death in brain cells affected with tau tangles.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Exactly how disturbances of production and aggregation of the Aβ peptide give rise to the pathology of Alzheimer's disease is not known.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The amyloid hypothesis (also known as the 'amyloid cascade hypothesis') posits that the accumulation of abnormally shaped Aβ peptides is the central event triggering the sequence of changes that eventually lead to neurodegeneration and dementia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Misfolded Aβ accumulates in the brain because it causes normal Aβ molecules to similarly misfold by a prion-like 'seeding' mechanism.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The aggregated Aβ takes the form of small oligomers (which are particularly toxic to neurons) and amyloid fibrils, the long polymers that are the main components of Aβ plaques.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Some researchers have argued that the amyloid fibrils bind up smaller oligomers and thus protect brain cells from the injurious effects of the oligomers.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] However, the plaques are not benign inasmuch as they are associated with abnormal neuronal processes and local inflammation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Whatever the relative influence of Aβ oligomers and fibrils, the presence of aggregated Aβ is associated with the disruption of neuronal metabolism and various other changes such as inflammation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Aβ also selectively builds up in mitochondria in the cells of Alzheimer's-affected brains, and it inhibits certain enzyme functions and the utilisation of glucose by neurons.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Evidence supports Aβ as playing a central role in the pathogenesis of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Iron dyshomeostasis is linked to disease progression in which an iron-dependent form of regulated cell death called ferroptosis could be involved.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Products of lipid peroxidation are also elevated in the Alzheimer's brain compared with controls.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Various inflammatory processes and cytokines also play a role in the pathology of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Inflammation is a general marker of tissue damage in any disease, and may be either secondary to tissue damage in Alzheimer's disease or a marker of an immunological response.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Cells that mediate neuroinflammation in Alzheimer's include microglia, astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, lymphocytes and myeloid cells.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] There is increasing evidence of a strong interaction between neurons and the immunological mechanisms in the brain.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Obesity and systemic inflammation may interfere with immunological processes which promote disease progression.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Microglia are especially important actors in the Alzheimer's-related inflammation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Microglia are the principal immunological cells of the central nervous system, serving as the tissue-resident macrophages of the brain; they are capable of recognizing and taking up Aβ through multiple pattern recognition receptors, making them central to amyloid clearance within the brain.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] However, microglia can also be a major source of pro-inflammatory mediators which can be deleterious to neurological function.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Microglia are topographically associated with aberrant deposits of tau and Aβ within the brain, even when each pathologic component occurs in distinct brain regions.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Microglial activation has been documented in people with mild cognitive impairment, despite a lack of detectable binding of a PET tracer for Aβ in the brain, suggesting that microglial dysfunction may precede plaque deposition as an inciting event in AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Alterations in the distribution of different neurotrophic factors and in the expression of their receptors, such as the brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF), have been described in Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] By the time the symptoms of Alzheimer's first appear, the complex degenerative mechanisms in the brain have been active for many years.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The absent or minor effect on cognitive function of monoclonal antibodies that promote Aβ clearance suggests reconsideration of the amyloid cascade hypothesis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Alzheimer's disease (AD) can be definitively diagnosed only with autopsy findings; in the absence of autopsy, clinical diagnoses of AD are "possible" or "probable", based on other findings.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Up to 23% of those clinically diagnosed with AD may be misdiagnosed and may have pathology suggestive of another condition with symptoms that mimic those of AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] AD is usually clinically diagnosed based on a person's medical history, observations from friends or relatives, and behavioral changes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The presence of characteristic neuropsychological changes with impairments in at least two cognitive domains that are severe enough to affect a person's functional abilities is required for the diagnosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Domains that may be impaired include memory (most commonly impaired), language, executive function, visuospatial functioning, or other areas of cognition.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The neurocognitive changes must be a decline from a prior level of function, and the diagnosis requires ruling out other common causes of neurocognitive decline.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Advanced medical imaging with computed tomography (CT) or magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), and with single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT) or positron emission tomography (PET), can be used to help exclude other cerebral pathology or subtypes of dementia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] On MRI or CT, Alzheimer's disease usually shows a generalised or focal cortical atrophy, which may be asymmetric.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Atrophy of the hippocampus is also commonly seen.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Brain imaging commonly also shows cerebrovascular disease, most commonly previous strokes (small or large territory strokes), and this is thought to be a contributing cause of many cases of dementia (up to 46% cases of dementia also have cerebrovascular disease on imaging).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] FDG-PET scan is not required for the diagnosis but it is sometimes used when standard testing is unclear.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] FDG-PET shows a bilateral, asymmetric, temporal and parietal reduced activity.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Advanced imaging may predict conversion from prodromal stages (mild cognitive impairment) to Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] FDA-approved radiopharmaceutical diagnostic agents used in PET for Alzheimer's disease are florbetapir (2012), flutemetamol (2013), florbetaben (2014), and flortaucipir (2020).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Because many insurance companies in the United States do not cover this procedure, its use in clinical practice is largely limited to clinical trials as of 2018.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Assessment of intellectual functioning, including memory testing, can further characterise the disease state.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Medical organizations have created diagnostic criteria to ease and standardise the diagnostic process for practising physicians.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Definitive diagnosis can only be confirmed with post-mortem evaluations when brain material is available and can be examined histologically for senile plaques and neurofibrillary tangles.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Eight intellectual domains are most commonly impaired in AD—memory, language, perceptual skills, attention, motor skills, orientation, problem solving and executive functional abilities, as listed in the fourth text revision of the DSM (DSM-IV-TR).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The DSM-5 defines criteria for probable or possible AD for both major and mild neurocognitive disorders.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Major or mild neurocognitive disorder must be present along with at least one cognitive deficit for a diagnosis of either probable or possible AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] For major neurocognitive disorder due to AD, probable Alzheimer's disease can be diagnosed if the individual has genetic evidence of AD or if two or more acquired cognitive deficits, and a functional disability that is not from another disorder, are present.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Otherwise, possible AD can be diagnosed as the diagnosis follows an atypical route.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The NIA-AA criteria are used mainly in research rather than in clinical assessments.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] They define AD through three major stages: preclinical, mild cognitive impairment (MCI), and Alzheimer's dementia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Diagnosis in the preclinical stage is complex and focuses on asymptomatic individuals; the latter two stages describe individuals experiencing symptoms, along with biomarkers, predominantly those for neuronal injury (mainly tau-related) and amyloid beta deposition.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The core clinical criteria itself rests on the presence of cognitive impairment without the presence of comorbidities.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The third stage is divided into probable and possible AD dementia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In probable AD dementia there is steady impairment of cognition over time and a memory-related or non-memory-related cognitive dysfunction.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In possible AD dementia, another causal disease such as cerebrovascular disease is present.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Neuropsychological tests including cognitive tests such as the mini–mental state examination (MMSE), the Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA) and the Mini-Cog are widely used to aid in diagnosis of the cognitive impairments in AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] These tests may not always be accurate, as they lack sensitivity to mild cognitive impairment, and can be biased by language or attention problems; more comprehensive test arrays are necessary for high reliability of results, particularly in the earliest stages of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Further neurological examinations are crucial in the differential diagnosis of Alzheimer's disease and other diseases.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Interviews with family members are used in assessment, and caregivers can supply important information on daily living abilities and on the decrease in the person's mental function.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] A caregiver's viewpoint is particularly important, since a person with Alzheimer's disease is commonly unaware of their deficits.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Many times, families have difficulties in the detection of initial dementia symptoms and may not communicate accurate information to a physician.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Supplemental testing can rule out other potentially treatable diagnoses and help avoid misdiagnoses.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Common supplemental tests include blood tests, thyroid function tests, as well as tests to assess vitamin B12 levels, rule out neurosyphilis and rule out metabolic problems (including tests for kidney function, electrolyte levels and for diabetes).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] MRI or CT scans might also be used to rule out other potential causes of the symptoms – including tumors or strokes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Delirium and depression can be common among individuals and are important to rule out.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Psychological tests for depression are used, since depression can either be concurrent with AD (see Depression of Alzheimer disease), an early sign of cognitive impairment, or even the cause.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Due to low accuracy, the C-PIB-PET scan is not recommended as an early diagnostic tool or for predicting the development of AD when people show signs of mild cognitive impairment (MCI).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The use of 18F-FDG PET scans, as a single test, to identify people who may develop Alzheimer's disease is not supported by evidence.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] In May 2025, the US FDA approved a blood test by Fujirebio Diagnostics' Lumipulse G pTau217/ß-Amyloid 1-42 Plasma Ratio diagnostic device for the early detection of amyloid plaques associated with AD in adults aged 55 years and older who are exhibiting signs and symptoms of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] There is no disease-modifying treatments proven to cure Alzheimer's disease, and because of this, AD research has focused on interventions to prevent the onset and progression.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] There is no evidence that supports any particular measure in preventing AD, and studies of measures to prevent the onset or progression have produced inconsistent results.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Epidemiological studies have proposed relationships between an individual's likelihood of developing AD and modifiable factors, such as medications, lifestyle, and diet.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] There are some challenges in determining whether interventions for AD act as a primary prevention method, preventing the disease itself, or a secondary prevention method, identifying the early stages of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] These challenges include duration of intervention, different stages of disease at which intervention begins, and lack of standardization of inclusion criteria regarding biomarkers specific for AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Further research is needed to determine factors that can help prevent AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Cardiovascular risk factors, such as hypercholesterolaemia, hypertension, diabetes, and smoking, are associated with a higher risk of onset and worsened course of AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The use of statins to lower cholesterol may be of benefit in AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Antihypertensive and antidiabetic medications in individuals without overt cognitive impairment may decrease the risk of dementia by influencing cerebrovascular pathology.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] More research is needed to examine the relationship with AD specifically; clarification of the direct role medications play versus other concurrent lifestyle changes (diet, exercise, smoking) is needed.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Depression is associated with an increased risk for AD; management with antidepressant medications may provide a preventative measure.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Historically, long-term usage of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) was thought to be associated with a reduced likelihood of developing AD, as it reduces inflammation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] NSAIDs do not appear to be useful as a treatment.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Additionally, because women have a higher incidence of AD than men, it was once thought that estrogen deficiency during menopause was a risk factor.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] There is a lack of evidence to show that hormone replacement therapy (HRT) in menopause decreases the risk of cognitive decline.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Certain lifestyle activities, such as physical and cognitive exercises, higher education and occupational attainment, cigarette smoking, stress, sleep, and the management of other comorbidities, including diabetes and hypertension, may affect the risk of developing AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Physical exercise is associated with a decreased rate of dementia, and is effective in reducing symptom severity in those with AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Memory and cognitive functions can be improved with aerobic exercises including brisk walking three times weekly for forty minutes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] It may also induce neuroplasticity of the brain.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Participating in mental exercises, such as reading, crossword puzzles, and chess have reported potential to be preventive.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Meeting the WHO recommendations for physical activity is associated with a lower risk of AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Higher education and occupational attainment, and participation in leisure activities, contribute to a reduced risk of developing AD, or of delaying the onset of symptoms.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] This is compatible with the cognitive reserve theory, which states that some life experiences result in more efficient neural functioning, providing the individual with a cognitive reserve that delays the onset of dementia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Education delays the onset of Alzheimer's disease syndrome without changing the duration of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Cessation in smoking may reduce the risk of developing AD, specifically in those who carry the APOE ɛ4 allele.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The increased oxidative stress caused by smoking results in downstream inflammatory or neurodegenerative processes that may increase risk of developing AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Avoidance of smoking, counseling and pharmacotherapies to quit smoking are used, and avoidance of environmental tobacco smoke is recommended.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Alzheimer's disease is associated with sleep disorders but the precise relationship is unclear.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] It was once thought that as people get older, the risk of developing sleep disorders and AD independently increase, but research suggests sleep disorders may be a risk factor for AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] One theory is that the mechanisms to increase clearance of toxic substances, including Aβ, are active during sleep.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] With decreased sleep, a person is increasing Aβ production and decreasing Aβ clearance, resulting in Aβ accumulation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Receiving adequate sleep (approximately 7–8 hours) every night has become a potential lifestyle intervention to prevent the development of AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Stress is a risk factor for the development of AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] The mechanism by which stress predisposes someone to the development of AD is unclear, but it is suggested that lifetime stressors may affect a person's epigenome, leading to an overexpression or underexpression of specific genes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Although the relationship of stress and AD is unclear, strategies to reduce stress and relax the mind may be helpful strategies in preventing the progression or Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p01] Meditation, for instance, is a helpful lifestyle change to support cognition and well-being, though further research is needed to assess long-term effects.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] There is no cure for AD; available treatments offer relatively small symptomatic benefits but remain palliative in nature.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Treatments can be divided into pharmaceutical, psychosocial, and caregiving.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Medications used to treat the cognitive symptoms of AD rather than the underlying cause include: four acetylcholinesterase inhibitors (tacrine, rivastigmine, galantamine, and donepezil) and memantine, an NMDA receptor antagonist.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The acetylcholinesterase inhibitors are intended for those with mild to severe AD, whereas memantine is intended for those with moderate or severe Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Reduction in the activity of the cholinergic neurons is a well-known feature of AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Acetylcholinesterase inhibitors are employed to reduce the rate at which the body breaks down acetylcholine (ACh), thereby increasing the concentration of ACh in the brain and combating the loss of ACh caused by the death of cholinergic neurons.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Evidence supports medical efficacy in mild to moderate AD, and somewhat in the advanced stage.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] This does not extend to delaying symptom onset.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Memantine is a noncompetitive NMDA receptor antagonist first used as an anti-influenza agent.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] It acts on the glutamatergic system by blocking NMDA receptors and inhibiting their overstimulation by glutamate.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Memantine has been reported to have a small benefit in the treatment of moderate to severe AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The combination of memantine and donepezil has been reported to be "of statistically significant but clinically marginal effectiveness".
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] An extract of *Ginkgo biloba* known as EGb 761 has been used for treating AD and other neuropsychiatric disorders.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] An umbrella review and a continuing education article differ as to whether it is effective in the treatment of AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Atypical antipsychotics are modestly useful in reducing aggression and psychosis in people with AD, but their advantages are offset by serious adverse effects, such as stroke, movement difficulties, or cognitive decline.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] They are recommended in dementia only after first-line therapies such as behavior modification have failed, and due to the risk of adverse effects, they should be used for the shortest amount of time possible.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Stopping antipsychotic use in this group of people appears to be safe.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The most common side effects are nausea and vomiting, both of which are linked to cholinergic excess.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] These side effects arise in approximately 10–20% of users, are mild to moderate in severity, and can be managed by slowly adjusting medication doses.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Less common secondary effects include muscle cramps, decreased heart rate (bradycardia), decreased appetite and weight, and increased gastric acid production.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Reported adverse events with memantine are infrequent and mild, including hallucinations, confusion, dizziness, headache, and fatigue.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Two monoclonal antibodies have been approved to target amyloid beta – donanemab and lecanemab – but as of 2025, their role in treatment is uncertain because of side effects, questions about efficacy, and cost.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Lecanemab is approved in the US, including a boxed warning about amyloid-related imaging abnormalities.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] A 2026 meta-analysis found that anti-amyloid antibodies have no effect in the treatment of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] A 2026 Cochrane review found no effect or at best small effect.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Anti-amyloid antibodies may cause harmful adverse effects.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Psychosocial interventions are used as an adjunct to pharmaceutical treatment and can be classified within behavior-, emotion-, cognition- or stimulation-oriented approaches.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Behavioral interventions attempt to identify and reduce the antecedents and consequences of problem behaviors.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] This approach has not reported success in improving overall functioning, but can help to reduce some specific problem behaviors, such as incontinence.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] There is a lack of high quality data on the effectiveness of these techniques in other behavior problems such as wandering.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Music therapy is effective in reducing behavioral and psychological symptoms.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Emotion-oriented interventions include reminiscence therapy, validation therapy, supportive psychotherapy, sensory integration, also called snoezelen, and simulated presence therapy.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] A Cochrane review has found no evidence that this is effective.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Reminiscence therapy (RT) involves the discussion of past experiences, individually or in groups, many times with the aid of photographs, household items, music and sound recordings, or other familiar items from the past.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] A 2018 review of the effectiveness of RT found that effects were inconsistent, small in size, and of doubtful clinical significance, and varied by setting.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Simulated presence therapy (SPT) is based on attachment theories and involves playing a recording with the voices of the closest relatives of the person with AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] There is partial evidence indicating that SPT may reduce challenging behaviors.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The aim of cognition-oriented treatments, which include reality orientation and cognitive retraining, is the reduction of cognitive deficits.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Reality orientation consists of the presentation of information about time, place, or person to ease the understanding of the person about his or her surroundings and his or her place in them.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] On the other hand, cognitive retraining tries to improve impaired capacities by exercising mental abilities.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Both have reported some efficacy in improving cognitive capacities.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Stimulation-oriented treatments include art, music, and pet therapies, exercise, and any other kind of recreational activities.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Stimulation has modest support for improving behavior, mood, and, to a lesser extent, function.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Nevertheless, as important as these effects are, the main support for the use of stimulation therapies is the change in the person's routine.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Caregiving is the ongoing physical, social, emotional support provided to people living with dementia, helping them carry out everyday activities.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Since AD has no cure and it gradually renders people incapable of tending to their own needs, caregiving is essentially the treatment and must be carefully managed over the course of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] During the early and moderate stages, modifications to the living environment and lifestyle can increase safety and reduce caretaker burden.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Examples of such modifications are the adherence to simplified routines, the placing of safety locks, the labeling of household items to cue the person with the disease or the use of modified daily life objects.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Per the American Academy of Family Physicians, the use of physical restraints is discouraged.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Use of the "VIPS" framework "(Valuing people, Individualised care, Personal perspectives, Social environment)" has been shown to reduce hours per day of restraint.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] If eating becomes problematic, food will need to be prepared in smaller pieces or even puréed.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] When swallowing difficulties arise, the use of feeding tubes may be required.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] In such cases, the medical efficacy and ethics of continuing feeding is an important consideration of the caregivers and family members.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] During the final stages of the disease, treatment is centred on relieving discomfort until death, often with the help of hospice.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The wellbeing of caregivers themselves is an important aspect of AD caregiving.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Long-term informal caregiving is associated with wide-ranging impacts on physical and mental health and on financial circumstances, collectively described as caregiver burden.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] A range of interventions can help alleviate burden and improve caregiver wellbeing.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Effective measures include complementary formal services, training and psychoeducation, psychological therapies such as cognitive behavioural therapy, and support groups.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Diet may be a modifiable risk factor for the development of Alzheimer's disease, but more research needs to be conducted.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The Mediterranean diet, and the DASH diet are both associated with less cognitive decline.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] A different approach has been to incorporate elements of both of these diets into one known as the MIND diet.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Results from large-scale epidemiological studies and clinical trials have not demonstrated an independent role for most individual dietary components.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The early stages of AD are difficult to diagnose.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] A definitive diagnosis is usually made once cognitive impairment compromises daily living activities, although the person may still be living independently.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The symptoms will progress from mild cognitive problems, such as memory loss, through increasing stages of cognitive and non-cognitive disturbances, eliminating any possibility of independent living, especially in the late stages of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Life expectancy of people with AD is reduced.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The normal life expectancy for 60 to 70-year-olds is 23 to 15 years; for 90-year-olds, it is 4.5 years.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Following AD diagnosis it ranges from 7 to 10 years for those in their 60s and early 70s (a loss of 13 to 8 years), to only about 3 years or less (a loss of 1.5 years) for those in their 90s.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] As of 1995, fewer than 3% of people lived more than fourteen years after diagnosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Disease features significantly associated with reduced survival are increased severity of cognitive impairment, decreased functional level, disturbances in the neurological examination, history of falls, malnutrition, dehydration and weight loss.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Other coincident diseases such as heart problems, diabetes, or history of alcohol abuse are also related with shortened survival.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] While the earlier the age at onset the higher the total survival years, life expectancy is particularly reduced when compared to the healthy population among those who are younger.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Men have a less favorable survival prognosis than women, even after controlling for age and some medical conditions.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] As of 2025, the reasons for the higher mortality in men are unknown.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] It has been speculated that men have different dementia risk factors than women, like traumatic brain injury.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Aspiration pneumonia is the most frequent immediate cause of death brought by AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] While the reasons behind the lower prevalence of cancer in AD patients remain unclear, some researchers hypothesize that biological mechanisms shared by both diseases might play a role.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] However, this requires further investigation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] In 2020, there were approximately 50 million people worldwide with Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The prevalence of AD in populations is dependent upon factors including incidence and survival.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Since the incidence of AD increases with age, prevalence depends on the mean age of the population for which prevalence is given.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Prevalence rates in less developed regions around the globe are lower.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Both the prevalence and incidence rates of AD are steadily increasing, and the prevalence rate is estimated to triple by 2050 reaching 152 million, compared to the 50 million people with AD globally in 2020.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Regarding incidence, where a disease-free population is followed over the years have shown rates between 10 and 15 per thousand person-years for all dementias and 5–8 for AD in Spain and Italy, which means that half of new dementia cases each year are Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Advancing age is a primary risk factor for the disease, and incidence rates are not equal for all ages: every 5 years after the age of 65, the risk of acquiring the disease approximately doubles, increasing from 3 to as much as 69 per thousand person-years.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] This difference has been thought to be due to women's longer life spans.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] According to one study, when adjusted for age, both sexes were affected by Alzheimer's at equal rates.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] However, many studies have found even higher age-adjusted numbers for women, including the Framingham study which found women to have almost twice the lifetime risk of men.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] As of 2025, it is unknown why women are more commonly affected by AD, although many theories exist, as mentioned in the section on causes above.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] There are also observable differences in the disease course, as tau protein accumulates faster in women than in men.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Also, presence of APOE4 increases AD risk more in women than in men.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Even if the same amount of AD pathology observed in a woman compared to a man, there is greater cognitive decline in a woman.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] This is relevant for therapy, like the timing of anti-tau treatments or menopausal hormone therapy: In the Canadian Longitudinal Study of Aging, women on MHT had higher memory scores than those who were not on MHT.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] In the United States, the risk of dying from AD in 2010 was 26% higher among the non-Hispanic white population than among the non-Hispanic black population, and the Hispanic population had a 30% lower risk than the non-Hispanic white population.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] However, much AD research remains to be done in minority groups, such as the African American, East Asian, and Hispanic/Latino populations.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Studies have reported that these groups are underrepresented in clinical trials and do not have the same risk of developing AD when carrying certain genetic risk factors (i.e.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] APOE4), compared to their caucasian counterparts.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] In the United States in 2020, AD dementia prevalence was estimated to be 5.3% for those in the 60–74 age group, with the rate increasing to 13.8% in the 74–84 group and to 34.6% in those greater than 85.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Estimates show that in 2024 there were nearly a million people living with AD and other dementias in the UK, with more than 800 000 in England.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] This is expected to rise to 1.4 million by 2040, with numbers doubling in England.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] In 2022 and 2023, dementia was the leading cause of death in England and Wales.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The ancient Greek and Roman philosophers and physicians associated old age with increasing dementia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] It was not until 1901 that German psychiatrist Alois Alzheimer identified the first case of what became known as Alzheimer's disease, named after him, in a fifty-year-old woman he called Auguste D.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] He followed her case until she died in 1906, when he first reported publicly on it.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] During the next five years, eleven similar cases were reported in the medical literature, some of them already using the term Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The disease was first described as a distinctive disease by Emil Kraepelin after suppressing some of the clinical (delusions and hallucinations) and pathological features (arteriosclerotic changes) contained in the original report of Auguste D.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] He included *Alzheimer's disease*, also named *presenile* dementia by Kraepelin, as a subtype of *senile dementia* in the eighth edition of his *Textbook of Psychiatry*, published on 15 July 1910.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] For most of the 20th century, the diagnosis of Alzheimer's disease was reserved for individuals between the ages of 45 and 65 who developed symptoms of dementia.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The terminology changed after 1977 when a conference on Alzheimer's disease concluded that the clinical and pathological manifestations of presenile and senile dementia were almost identical, although the authors also added that this did not rule out the possibility that they had different causes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] This eventually led to the diagnosis of *Alzheimer's disease* independent of age.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The term *senile dementia of the Alzheimer type* (SDAT) was used for a time to describe the condition in those over 65, with classical Alzheimer's disease being used to describe those who were younger.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Eventually, the term Alzheimer's disease was formally adopted in medical nomenclature to describe individuals of all ages with a characteristic common symptom pattern, disease course, and neuropathology.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] These criteria require that the presence of cognitive impairment, and a suspected dementia syndrome, be confirmed by neuropsychological testing for a clinical diagnosis of possible or probable Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] A histopathologic confirmation including a microscopic examination of brain tissue is required for a definitive diagnosis.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Good statistical reliability and validity have been reported between the diagnostic criteria and definitive histopathological confirmation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] People living with AD and other forms of dementia and their unpaid carers might face inequalities in access to and the quality of care and support services.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] These inequalities can depend on various factors, including socio-economic background, housing situation, education level, gender, and race.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] People might have differences in how easily they can access AD services based on where they live.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] On a global level, people in low-and middle-income countries have fewer available facilities and services, and have greater difficulties accessing these than people living in high-income countries.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] As a result of AD and other forms of dementia being less recognised and treated in the healthcare systems of these countries, the level of awareness of AD as something caused by disease is relatively lower.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] At the same time, the local socio-cultural understandings of aging, senility, and eldercare may have larger effects on care provision and the reception of medical services.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] On a national level, people with AD might have unequal access to care based on where they live.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] This can manifest on a regional level, with people in rural areas facing more difficulties than those in urban areas.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Inequalities can also affect smaller local units as well, for example people living in the same city might receive different or less frequent care based on their postcodes or the street they live in.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Inequalities also affect people with AD from ethnic minority groups.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Those coming from a minority background often receive lower quality care, they are less likely to get anti-AD medications compared to their White counterparts.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Furthermore, when they are prescribed medication, they are less likely to adhere to the treatment due to various factors and barriers such as the quality of interaction with healthcare providers, distrust in doctors, worries about retaining personal autonomy, stigmas and different beliefs.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Dementia, and specifically Alzheimer's disease, may be among the most costly diseases for societies worldwide.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] As populations age, these costs will probably increase and become an important social problem and economic burden.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Costs associated with AD include direct and indirect medical costs, which vary between countries depending on social care for a person with AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Direct costs include doctor visits, hospital care, medical treatments, nursing home care, specialised equipment, and household expenses.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Indirect costs include the cost of informal care and the loss in productivity of informal caregivers.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] In the United States as of 2019, informal (family) care is estimated to constitute nearly three-fourths of caregiving for people with AD at a cost of US$234 billion per year and approximately 18.5 billion hours of care.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] The cost to society worldwide to care for individuals with AD is projected to increase nearly ten-fold, and reach about US$9.1 trillion by 2050.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Costs for those with more severe dementia or behavioral disturbances are higher and are related to the additional caregiving time to provide physical care.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Documentaries on Alzheimer's disease include *Malcolm and Barbara: A Love Story* (1999) and *Malcolm and Barbara: Love's Farewell* (2007), both featuring Malcolm Pointon.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Alzheimer's disease has also been portrayed in music by English musician the Caretaker in releases such as *Persistent Repetition of Phrases* (2008), *An Empty Bliss Beyond This World* (2011), and *Everywhere at the End of Time* (2016–2019).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Paintings depicting the disorder include the late works by American artist William Utermohlen, who drew self-portraits from 1995 to 2000 as an experiment of showing his disease through art.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Specific medications that may reduce the risk or progression of Alzheimer's disease include those that impact Aβ plaques, inflammation, APOE, neurotransmitter receptors, neurogenesis, growth factors or hormones.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] Machine learning algorithms with electronic health records are studied as a way to predict Alzheimer's disease earlier.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/alzheimer-s-disease-p02] As of 2025, 182 clinical trials were testing 138 drugs against multiple targets.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Apo-E belongs to a family of fat-binding proteins called apolipoproteins.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] In the circulation, it is present as part of several classes of lipoprotein particles, including chylomicron remnants, VLDL, IDL, and some HDL.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Apo-E interacts significantly with the low-density lipoprotein receptor (LDLR), which is essential for the normal processing (catabolism) of triglyceride-rich lipoproteins.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] In peripheral tissues, Apo-E is primarily produced by the liver and macrophages, and mediates cholesterol metabolism.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] In the central nervous system, Apo-E is mainly produced by astrocytes and transports cholesterol to neurons via Apo-E receptors, which are members of the low density lipoprotein receptor gene family.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Apo-E is the principal cholesterol carrier in the brain.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Apo-E qualifies as a checkpoint inhibitor of the classical complement pathway by complex formation with activated C1q.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Apolipoproteins are not unique to mammals.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Many terrestrial and marine vertebrates have versions of them.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] It is believed that *APOE* arose via gene duplications of *APOC1* before the fish–tetrapod split ca.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Proteins similar in function have been found in choanoflagellates, suggesting that they are a very old class of proteins predating the dawn of all living animals.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] The three major human alleles (*E4*, *E3*, *E2*) arose after the primate–human split around 7.5 million years ago.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] These alleles are the by-product of non-synonymous mutations which led to changes in functionality.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] After the primate–human split, there were four amino acid changes in the human lineage, three of which had no effect on protein function (V174L, A18T, A135V).
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] The fourth substitution (T61R) traded a threonine for an arginine altering the protein's functionality.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] This substitution occurred somewhere in the 6 million year gap between the primate–human split and the Denisovan–human split, since exactly the same substitutions were found in Denisovan *APOE*.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] About 220,000 years ago, an arginine to cysteine substitution took place at amino acid 112 (Arg112Cys) of the *APOE4* gene, and this resulted in the *E3* allele.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Finally, 80,000 years ago, an arginine to cysteine substitution at amino acid 158 (Arg158Cys) of the *APOE3* gene created the *E2* allele.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] The gene, *APOE*, is mapped to chromosome 19 in a cluster with the apolipoprotein C1 (*APOC1*) gene and the apolipoprotein C2 (*APOC2*) gene.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] The *APOE* gene consists of four exons and three introns, totaling 3597 base pairs.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] *APOE* is transcriptionally activated by the liver X receptor (an important regulator of cholesterol, fatty acid, and glucose homeostasis) and peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor γ, nuclear receptors that form heterodimers with retinoid X receptors.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] In melanocytic cells *APOE* gene expression may be regulated by MITF.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Apoe-E is 299 amino acids long and contains multiple amphipathic α-helices.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] According to crystallography studies, a hinge region connects the N- and C-terminal regions of the protein.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] The N-terminal region (residues 1–167) forms an anti-parallel four-helix bundle such that the non-polar sides face inside the protein.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Meanwhile, the C-terminal domain (residues 206–299) contains three α-helices which form a large exposed hydrophobic surface and interact with those in the N-terminal helix bundle domain through hydrogen bonds and salt-bridges.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] The C-terminal region also contains a low density lipoprotein receptor (LDLR)-binding site.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] There are several low-frequency polymorphisms of APOE.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] APOE5 comes in two subtypes E5f and E5s, based on migration rates.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] APOE5 E5f and APOE7 combined were found in 2.8% of Japanese males.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] APOE7 is a mutation of APOE3 with two lysine residues replacing glutamic acid residues at positions 244 and 245.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Many of the studies cited that purport these adverse outcomes are from single studies that have not been replicated and the research is based on unchecked assumptions about this isoform.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] As of 2007, there was no evidence that APOE polymorphisms influence cognition in younger age groups (other than possible better visual working memory in younger APOE4 age groups), nor that the APOE4 isoform places individuals at increased risk for any infectious disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] However, the association between the APOE4 allele and Alzheimer's disease has been shown to be weaker in minority groups differently compared to their Caucasian counterparts.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Hispanics/Latinos and African Americans who were homozygous for the APOE4 allele had 2.2 and 5.7 times the odds, respectively of developing Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] The homozygous APOE4 allele has an even stronger effect in East Asian populations, with Japanese populations have 33 times the odds compared to the heterozygous population.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Caucasians who were homozygous for the allele had 12.5 times the odds.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] As a component of the lipoprotein lipid transport system, APOE facilitates the transport of lipids, fat-soluble vitamins, and cholesterol via the blood.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] It interacts with the LDL receptor to facilitate endocytosis of VLDL remnants.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] It is synthesized principally in the liver, but has also been found in other tissues such as the brain, kidneys, and spleen.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] APOE synthesized in the liver associates with HDL which can then distribute it to newly formed VLDL or chylomicron particles to facilitate their eventual uptake by the liver.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] In the nervous system, non-neuronal cell types, most notably astroglia and microglia, are the primary producers of APOE, while neurons preferentially express the receptors for APOE.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] There are seven currently identified mammalian receptors for APOE which belong to the evolutionarily conserved LDLR family.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] APOE was initially recognized for its importance in lipoprotein metabolism and cardiovascular disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Defects in APOE result in familial dysbetalipoproteinemia aka type III hyperlipoproteinemia (HLP III), in which increased plasma cholesterol and triglycerides are the consequence of impaired clearance of chylomicron, VLDL and LDL.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] More recently, it has been studied for its role in several biological processes not directly related to lipoprotein transport, including Alzheimer's disease (AD), immunoregulation, and cognition.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Though the exact mechanisms remain to be elucidated, isoform 4 of APOE, encoded by an APOE allele, has been associated with increased calcium ion levels and apoptosis following mechanical injury.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] APOE is produced by macrophages and APOE secretion has been shown to be restricted to classical monocytes in PBMC, and the secretion of APOE by monocytes is down regulated by inflammatory cytokines and upregulated by TGF-beta.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] As of 2012, the E4 variant was the largest known genetic risk factor for late-onset sporadic Alzheimer's disease (AD) in a variety of ethnic groups.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] However, the E4 variant does not correlate with risk in every population.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Nigerian people have the highest observed frequency of the *APOE4* allele in world populations, but AD is rare among them.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] This may be due to their low cholesterol levels.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Caucasian and Japanese carriers of two E4 alleles have between 10 and 30 times the risk of developing AD by 75 years of age, as compared to those not carrying any E4 alleles.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] This may be caused by an interaction with amyloid.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] There is a sex specific effect, as presence of APOE4 increases AD risk more in women than in men.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Alzheimer's disease is characterized by build-ups of aggregates of the peptide beta-amyloid, the breakdown of which Apolipoprotein E enhances, both within and between cells.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] The isoform APOE-ε4 is not as effective as the others at promoting this breakdown, resulting in increased vulnerability to AD in individuals with that gene variation.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Although 40–65% of AD patients have at least one copy of the ε4 allele, *APOE4* is not a determinant of the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] At least one-third of patients with AD are *APOE4* negative and some *APOE4* homozygotes never develop the disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Yet those with two ε4 alleles have up to 20 times the risk of developing AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] There is also evidence that the *APOE2* allele may serve a protective role in AD.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Thus, the genotype most at risk for Alzheimer's disease and at an earlier age is APOE4,4.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Using genotype APOE3,3 as a benchmark (with the persons who have this genotype regarded as having a risk level of 1.0) and for white populations only, individuals with genotype APOE4,4 have an odds ratio of 14.9 of developing Alzheimer's disease.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Individuals with the APOE3,4 genotype face an odds ratio of 3.2, and people with a copy of the 2 allele and the 4 allele (APOE2,4), have an odds ratio of 2.6.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Persons with one copy each of the 2 allele and the 3 allele (APOE2,3) have an odds ratio of 0.6.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Persons with two copies of the 2 allele (APOE2,2) also have an odds ratio of 0.6.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Projecting from their data, some researchers have suggested that lowering serum cholesterol levels may reduce a person's risk for Alzheimer's disease, even if they have two ApoE4 alleles, thus reducing the risk from nine or ten times the odds of getting AD down to just two times the odds.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Women are more likely to develop AD than men across most ages and APOE genotypes.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] Premorbid women with the ε4 allele have significantly more neurological dysfunction than men.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] With the approval of the first disease-modifying therapies for Alzheimer's disease based on monoclonal antibodies against amyloid-beta, which delay disease progression, APOE genotyping has also become important in assessing a patient's risk of side effects under therapy.
[src:alzheimer-s-disease/apoe-e4] The applicant for this medicinal product is Eisai GmbH.
